# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: israel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] An earthquake struck the Jordan Rift Valley on December 5, AD 1033 and caused extreme devastation in the Levant region.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] It was part of a sequence of four strong earthquakes in the region between 1033 and 1035.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Scholars have estimated the moment magnitude to be greater than 7.0 Mw and evaluated the Modified Mercalli intensity to X (*Extreme*).
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] It triggered a tsunami along the Mediterranean coast, causing damage and fatalities.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] At least 70,000 people were killed in the disaster.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] In the past 2,000 years of human history, documented earthquakes have been associated with the 1,100 km (680 mi) long Dead Sea Transform Fault System, a left-lateral transform boundary.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Since the early Miocene, the fault system has accounted for between 110 km (68 mi) and 70–80 km (43–50 mi) of left-lateral displacement between the African and Arabian plates.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] While left-lateral strike-slip is dominant, the fault also displays features of normal and thrust faulting.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] The fault displays varying slip rates across its segments, 2–10 mm (0.079–0.394 in) per year.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] The Jordan Valley fault forms part of the larger system of faults that is collectively known as the Dead Sea Transform.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] This segment is 110 km (68 mi) long and trends north–south; beginning at the Dead Sea and terminating at the Sea of Galilee.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] The earthquake is thought to have ruptured the entire Jordan Valley Fault segment, based on reports of heavy damage reported from the Dead Sea to the Sea of Galilee.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] The historical record also showed that the pattern of damage was similar to another earthquake in AD 749.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Both the 749 AD and 1033 AD earthquakes ruptured the Jordan Valley Faults with magnitudes exceeding 7.0.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Earlier earthquakes in 31 BC and 363 AD are thought to have been caused by the same segment rupturing.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Paleoseismological studies near Jericho and the Sea of Galilee revealed evidence of surface ruptures.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Evident in the sedimentary layers are also signs of disturbed sediments thought to be caused by the earthquake.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Little research has addressed the magnitude of the earthquake, and there is a large variation in the range of estimated magnitudes.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] A 2004 study by Migowski and others estimated the magnitude at 7.1, based on studies of disturbed sedimentary layers.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] The magnitude has also been estimated at 6.0 to 7.1, although these figures has had their reliability and credibility questioned.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Italy's National Institute of Geophysics and Volcanology estimated an equivalent magnitude based on macroseismic observations (Me) of 7.3, and a 2020 earthquake catalog estimated that the earthquake had a moment magnitude of 7.3.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Heavy damage was reported in a north–south trend for 190 km (120 mi) from the Dead Sea to the Sea of Galilee.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] One-third of the city of Ramla was destroyed.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Half of Nablus was destroyed and 300 residents died.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] The landscape around the city was also devastated.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Acre experienced great damage and a high death toll.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] The cities of Banias and Jericho were also among those who suffered the greatest destruction.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] A landslide buried the village of al-Badan, killing all its residents and livestock.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Landslides also destroyed other villages and killed most of their population.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] In Syria, entire villages were "swallowed" by the earth, causing fatalities.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] In Gaza, the Great Mosque of Gaza and the surrounding minarets collapsed.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] A lighthouse in the city sustained heavy damage.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Reports of serious damage also came from Ascalon.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Damage was reported as far away as Egypt.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Alsinawi and others reported a death toll of 70,000.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Parts of the Walls of Jerusalem collapsed and many churches were damaged.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] A side of the Temple Mount and the Mihrab Daud, located near the Jaffa Gate, collapsed.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] It is believed to be the largest restoration project in the city's history.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] The Dome of the Rock was enforced with wooden beams to strengthen the structure.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Wooden beams and mosaics were added to the al-Aqsa Mosque.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Solomon's Stables and al-Aqsa Mosque were among the structures that underwent restoration.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Hisham's Palace in Jericho was destroyed; it was previously thought that the palace was destroyed during the AD 749 earthquake, but the relatively low intensity (VII) suggest it was not the responsible earthquake.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Academic studies noted fracture alignments on the ruin floor.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Evidence of column and wall failures were present.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Geological faulting was also found in the excavated area; the ruins displayed up to 10 cm (3.9 in) of left-lateral faulting.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Human remains discovered beneath the rubble of a collapsed arch were possibly caused by the earthquake.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] The Modified Mercalli intensity at the palace was assigned IX–X.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] It is possible that the palace site was abandoned after the earthquake and reoccupied sometime later.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] A tsunami struck the coastal city of Acre.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] It was reported that the city port became dry for an hour, and a large wave arrived, partially destroying it.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Waves were also reported along the coast of Lebanon.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Greek seismologist Nicholas Ambraseys reported that the tsunami caused no damage or casualties inland, but this information is thought to be in confusion with another earthquake in 1068.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] The only tsunami casualties were those who scoured the exposed seafloor and drowned when it arrived.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Additional shocks in April or May 1035 caused further damage and might be associated with tsunamis.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] The 1033 AD event was the last large earthquake on the Jordan Valley Fault.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Given the estimated slip rate is 4.9 ± 0.2 mm (0.1929 ± 0.0079 in) per year, approximately 5 m (16 ft) of potential slip has been accumulated.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] An estimated 3.5–5 m (11–16 ft) of slip could be produced during a future earthquake along a 110 km (68 mi) × 20 km (12 mi) fault area.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Such an event would suggest an earthquake of Mw 7.4, posing a great seismic threat to the region.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] In late 2020, researchers at Tel Aviv University said that an earthquake of magnitude 6.5 is expected to occur in the area, resulting in many fatalities.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Researchers also stated that the frequency of large earthquakes in the region is significantly underestimated.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Previous studies suggested a recurrence interval of 10,000 years for magnitude 7.5 earthquakes, but the researchers said the figure was 1,300 to 1,400 years.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Yosef Shapira, the then State Comptroller of Israel, said that a major earthquake in Israel could kill up to 7,000 people if safety recommendations are not enforced.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Reports of the years 2001, 2004 and 2011 found that the Israeli government did not fund any retrofitting works to old construction.
[src:israel/1033-jordan-valley-earthquake] Although the government said in 2008 that it would retrofit hospitals and schools, no major changes were made.
[src:israel/1517-hebron-attacks] An account of the event, recorded by Japheth ben Manasseh in 1518, mentions how the onslaught was initiated by Turkish troops led by Murad Bey, the deputy of the Sultan from Jerusalem.
[src:israel/1517-hebron-attacks] Jews were attacked, beaten and raped, and many were killed as their homes and businesses were looted and pillaged.
[src:israel/1517-hebron-attacks] It has been suggested that the stable financial position of the Hebronite Jews at the time was what attracted the Turkish soldiers to engage in the mass plunder.
[src:israel/1517-hebron-attacks] Others suggest the attack could have in fact taken place in the midst of a localised conflict, an uprising by the Mamluks against the new Ottoman rulers.
[src:israel/1517-hebron-attacks] Those who survived the calamity fled to Beirut and Jews only returned to Hebron 16 years later in 1533.
[src:israel/1517-safed-attacks] The **Safed attacks** were an incident that took place in Safed soon after the Turkish Ottomans had ousted the Mamluks and taken Levant during the Ottoman–Mamluk War in 1517.
[src:israel/1517-safed-attacks] At the time the town had roughly 300 Jewish households.
[src:israel/1517-safed-attacks] The severe blow took place as Mamluks clashed bloodily with the new Ottoman authorities.
[src:israel/1517-safed-attacks] The view that the riot's impact on the Jews of Safed was severe is contested.
[src:israel/1517-safed-attacks] Historians link the event to the general conflict taking place in the country between the incoming Ottoman regime and its opponents and note that the Jews suffered maltreatment during the war.
[src:israel/1517-safed-attacks] Accounts of the attack against the Jews in Safed were recorded by historian Rabbi Elijah Capsali of Candia, (Crete) and Rabbi Joseph Garson, who were living in Damascus at the time.
[src:israel/1517-safed-attacks] According to these reports, many Jews were killed and left injured.
[src:israel/1517-safed-attacks] They were compelled to flee the city and their property was plundered.
[src:israel/1517-safed-attacks] Scholars debate whether or not the event led to a decline in the Jewish population of Safed, but all agree that a few years later, Jews had re-established a significant presence in the city.
[src:israel/1517-safed-attacks] The attack may have been initiated by retreating Mamluk soldiers who accused the Jews of treacherously aiding the Turkish invaders, with Arabs from the surrounding villages joining the melee.
[src:israel/1517-safed-attacks] Alternatively, the attack occurred during an attempt by local Mamluk *sheikhs* to reassert their control after being removed from power by the incoming Turks.
[src:israel/1517-safed-attacks] David suggests that the violence may have erupted after rumours of an Ottoman defeat in Egypt led to clashes between supporters of the old regime and those who backed the newly imposed Turkish authority.
[src:israel/1517-safed-attacks] Supporters of the deposed Mamluk governor attacked Ottoman officials and after having murdered the Ottoman governor, the mob turned upon the Jews and rampaged through the Jewish quarter, the Jews suffering particular maltreatment.
[src:israel/1517-safed-attacks] Many Jews were reportedly killed, while others were wounded or had their property pillaged.
[src:israel/1517-safed-attacks] According to Garson, the Jews were "evicted from their homes, robbed and plundered, and they fled naked to the villages without any provisions." Many subsequently fled the city, but the community was soon rehabilitated with the financial help of Egyptian Jewry.
[src:israel/1517-safed-attacks] The many Jews who had fled and sought refuge in neighbouring villages returned, and within 8 years the community had reestablished itself, exceeding the former level of 300 households.
[src:israel/1517-safed-attacks] The Ottoman overthrow of the Mamluks brought about important changes.
[src:israel/1517-safed-attacks] Under the earlier dynasty, Egyptian Jews were guided by their *Nagid*, a rabbi also exercising the functions of a prince-judge.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-safed] The **1660 destruction of Safed** occurred during the Druze power struggle in Mount Lebanon, at the time of the rule of Ottoman sultan Mehmed IV.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-safed] The towns of Safed and nearby Tiberias, with substantial Jewish communities, were destroyed in the turmoil, a small Jewish community surviving in Safed, but Tiberias, a Jewish town at the time, losing almost its entire population.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-safed] Only a few of the former residents of Safed returned to the town after the destruction.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-safed] Gershom Scholem considers the 1662 reports about the destruction of Safed as "exaggerated".
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-safed] The community, however, recovered within several years, whereas Tiberias lay in waste for decades.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-safed] Safed's central role in Jewish life in Galilee declined after the late 16th century, when it had been a major city with a population of 15,000 Jews.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-safed] By the second half of the 17th century Safed still had a majority Jewish community with 200 "houses" (multiple family units) and some 4,000 to 5,000 Jewish residents, while about 100 "houses" in the town were Muslim.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-safed] The district was under control of Druze emirs from the Maan family until 1660, when the Ottomans sought to regain local control by reorganizing the sanjaks of Safed and Sidon-Beirut into the province of Sidon.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-safed] From the 1658 death of Emir Mulhim Ma'n to 1667, a struggle for power between his sons and other Ottoman-backed Druze rulers took place in the region.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-safed] Mulhim's son Ahmad Maʿn emerged victorious among the Druze, but the Maʿnīs lost control of the area and retreated to the Shuf mountains and Kisrawan.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-safed] In the 2nd half of the 17th century, Safed became the capital of the Ottoman sanjak of the same name.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-safed] Adler, Franco and Mendelssohn claim that the destruction of Safed took place in 1660, Mendelssohn writing that the Jews of Safed "had suffered severely" when the city had been destroyed by the Arabs.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-safed] Gershom Scholem places the attack in 1662, and Rappel writes that by 1662 both Safed and Tiberias were destroyed, with only a few of former Safed's Jewish residents to return to the town.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-safed] A publication by the General Council of the Jewish Community of Eretz Yisrael states that the Druze raided and destroyed both Safed and Tiberias in 1662, "and the inhabitants fled to the adjacent villages, to Sidon or to Jerusalem".
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-safed] Rosanes brings an account of Safed's Jewish community "utter destruction" in his book "History of the Jews in Turkish realm".
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-safed] However, Scholem writes that the reports of the "utter destruction" of the Jewish community in Safed in this time period "seem greatly exaggerated, and the conclusions based on them are false." He points out that Sabbatai Sevi's mystical movement was active in Safed in 1665.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-safed] Only a few of the former residents of Safed had returned to the town after the destruction.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-safed] Altogether, the town's Jewish community kept existing despite the events, with Barnai saying that "in the second half of the 17th century the Jewish presence in Palestine dwindled, and the Jewish presence in the Galilee also shrank.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-tiberias] The **1660 destruction of Tiberias** occurred during the Druze power struggle in the Galilee, in the same year as the destruction of Safed.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-tiberias] The destruction of Tiberias by the Druze resulted in abandonment of the city by its Jewish community, until it was rebuilt by Zahir al-Umar in early 18th century.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-tiberias] Altshuler however attributes the destruction of Tiberias in 1660 to an earthquake.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-tiberias] The destruction could have also been a combination of both events.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-tiberias] As the Ottoman Empire expanded along the southern Mediterranean coast under sultan Selim I, the Catholic Monarchs began establishing Inquisition commissions.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-tiberias] Many *Conversos*, (*Marranos* and *Moriscos*) and Sephardic Jews fled to the Ottoman provinces, settling at first in Constantinople, Salonika, Sarajevo, Sofia and in Anatolia.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-tiberias] The sultan encouraged them to settle in Palestine.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-tiberias] In 1558, a Portuguese-born marrano, Doña Gracia, was granted tax collecting rights in Tiberias and its surrounding villages by Suleiman the Magnificent.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-tiberias] She envisaged the town becoming a refuge for Jews and obtained a permit to establish Jewish autonomy there.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-tiberias] In 1561 her nephew Joseph Nasi, the sultan-appointed lord of Tiberias, encouraged Jews to settle in Tiberias.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-tiberias] Securing a *firman* from the sultan, he and Joseph ben Ardut or ibn Adret (converso name: Pomar), whom he sent to Tiberias, rebuilt the city walls and laid the groundwork for a textile (silk) industry, planting mulberry trees and urging craftsmen to move there.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-tiberias] In 1624, when the sultan recognized Fakhr-al-Din II as lord of Arabistan (a specially created realm stretching from Aleppo to the borders of Egypt), the Druze leader made Tiberias his capital.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-tiberias] The destruction of Tiberias by the Druze resulted in the Jewish community fleeing entirely.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-tiberias] Unlike Tiberias, which became desolate for many years, the nearby city of Safed recovered from its destruction by Druze in 1660 relatively quickly, not becoming entirely abandoned, remaining an important Jewish center in the Galilee.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-tiberias] In the 1720s, Zahir al-Umar, a Bedouin ruler of Ottoman Galilee, fortified Tiberias and signed an agreement with the neighboring Bedouin tribes to prevent looting.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-tiberias] Richard Pococke, who visited Tiberias in 1738, witnessed the building of a fort to the north of the city, and the strengthening of the old walls, attributing it to a dispute with the pasha (ruler) of Damascus.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-tiberias] Under Zahir's patronage, Jewish families were encouraged to settle in Tiberias.
[src:israel/1660-destruction-of-tiberias] He invited Chaim Abulafia of Smyrna to rebuild the Jewish community.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The **1920 Nebi Musa riots** or **1920 Jerusalem riots** took place in the British-controlled part of Occupied Enemy Territory Administration from 4 to 7 April 1920 in and around the Old City of Jerusalem.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Five Jews were killed and several hundred injured; four Arabs were killed and 18 injured; seven Britons were injured.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The riots coincided with and are named after the Nebi Musa festival, which was held every year on Easter Sunday, and followed rising tensions in Arab–Jewish relations.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The riots came shortly after the Battle of Tel Hai amid increasing pressure on Arab nationalists in Syria in the course of the Franco-Syrian War.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Arab religious leaders gave speeches during the festival (in which large numbers of Muslims traditionally gathered for a religious procession) that included slogans referencing Zionist immigration and previous confrontations over outlying Jewish villages in the Galilee.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The trigger that turned the procession into a riot is not known with certainty.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The British military administration of Palestine was criticized for withdrawing troops from inside Jerusalem and because it was slow to regain control.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] As a result of the riots, trust among the British, Jews, and Arabs eroded.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] One consequence was that the region's Jewish community increased moves towards an autonomous infrastructure and security apparatus parallel to that of the British administration.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] In its wake, sheikhs of 82 villages around the city and Jaffa, claiming to represent 70% of the population, issued a document protesting the demonstrations against the Jews.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] This condemnation may have been procured with bribes.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Notwithstanding the riots, the Jewish community held elections for the Assembly of Representatives on 19 April 1920 among Jews everywhere in Palestine except Jerusalem, where they were delayed to 3 May.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The riots also preceded the San Remo conference, which was held from 19 to 26 April 1920, and at which the fate of the Middle East was to be decided.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] In particular, the collapse of the Ottoman Empire led to an undertaking by the victorious powers, predominantly Great Britain and France, to assume a 'holy mission of civilization' in the power vacuum of the Middle East.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Under the Balfour Declaration, a homeland for the Jewish people was to be created in Palestine.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The principle of self-determination affirmed by the League of Nations was not to be applied to Palestine, given the foreseeable rejection by the people of Zionism, which the British sponsored.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] These post-World War I arrangements both for Palestine and other Arab societies led to a radicalization of the Arab world.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] On 1 March 1920, the death of Joseph Trumpeldor in the Battle of Tel Hai at the hands of a Shia group from Southern Lebanon caused deep concern among Jewish leaders, who made numerous requests to the OETA administration to address the Yishuv's security and forbid a pro-Syrian public rally.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Communiqués had been issued about foreseeable troubles among Arabs, and between Arabs and Jews.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] To Weizmann and the Jewish leadership, these developments were reminiscent of instructions that Russian generals had issued on the eve of pogroms.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] In the meantime, local Arab expectations had been raised to a pitch by the declaration of the Syrian Congress on 7 March of the independence of the region of Syria in the Kingdom of Syria, with Faisal as its king, that included the British-controlled territory within its claimed domain.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] On 7 and 8 March, demonstrations took place in all cities of Palestine, shops were closed and many Jews were attacked.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Jewish leaders requested that OETA authorise the arming of the Jewish defenders to make up for the lack of adequate British troops.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Although this request was declined, Ze'ev Jabotinsky, together with Pinhas Rutenberg, led an effort to openly train Jewish volunteers in self-defense, an effort of which the Zionist Commission kept the British informed.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Many of the volunteers were members of the Maccabi sports club and some of them were veterans of the Jewish Legion.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Their month of training largely consisted of calisthenics and hand to hand combat with sticks.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] By the end of March, about 600 were said to be performing military drills daily in Jerusalem.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Jabotinsky and Rutenberg also began organizing the collection of arms.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The Nebi Musa festival was an annual spring Muslim festival that began on the Friday before Good Friday and included a procession to the Nebi Musa shrine (tomb of Moses) near Jericho.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] It had apparently existed since the time of Saladin.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Arab educator and essayist Khalil al-Sakakini described how tribes and caravans would come with banners and weapons.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The Ottoman Turks usually deployed thousands of soldiers and even artillery to keep order in the narrow streets of Jerusalem during the Nebi Musa procession.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] However, Storrs issued a warning to Arab leaders, but deployed only 188 policemen.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] By 10:30 a.m. on Sunday, 4 April 1920, 60,000–70,000 Arabs had congregated in the city square for the Nebi Musa festival, and groups had been attacking Jews in the Old City's alleys for over an hour.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] A speech marked by anti-Zionist rhetoric was delivered by Amin al-Husayni from the balcony of the Arab Club.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Musa al-Husayni, his uncle, the mayor, was also with him and spoke from the municipal building's balcony in similar terms.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] According to testimony given by Fayyad al-Bakri to the Palin Commission, however, the rioting began when the Hebron banner he was holding while standing on Jaffa Street outside the Crédit Lyonnais Bank was spat on by a Jew and when the latter was pushed away, Jewish bystanders began throwing stones.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The editor of the newspaper *Suriya al-Janubia* (*Southern Syria*), Aref al-Aref, another Arab Club member, delivered a speech on horseback at the Jaffa Gate.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] According to Benny Morris, he said "If we don't use force against the Zionists and against the Jews, we will never be rid of them", while Bernard Wasserstein wrote "he seems to have co-operated with the police, and there is no evidence that he actively instigated violence".
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] In fact, Wasserstein adds, "Zionist intelligence reports of this period are unanimous in stressing that he spoke repeatedly against violence".
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The crowd reportedly shouted "Independence!
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Independence!" and "Palestine is our land, the Jews are our dogs!" Arab police joined in applause, and violence started.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The local Arab population ransacked the Jewish Quarter of Jerusalem.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The Torath Chaim Yeshiva was raided, and Torah scrolls were torn and thrown on the floor, and the building then set alight.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] During the next three hours, 160 Jews were injured.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] "[A] riot broke out, the people began to run about and stones were thrown at the Jews.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The shops were closed and there were screams. ...
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] I saw a Zionist soldier covered in dust and blood. ...
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Afterwards, I saw one Hebronite approach a Jewish shoeshine boy, who hid behind a sack in one of the wall's comers next to Jaffa Gate, and take his box and beat him over the head.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] He screamed and began to run, his head bleeding and the Hebronite left him and returned to the procession. ...
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] 's religion was born with the sword". ...
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The British imposed a nighttime curfew on Sunday night and arrested several dozen Arab rioters, but on Monday morning they were allowed to attend morning prayers and were then released.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Arabs continued to attack Jews and break into their homes, especially in Arab-majority mixed buildings.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] On Monday, as disturbances grew worse, the Old City was sealed off by British authorities and no one was allowed to exit the area.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Martial law was declared, but looting, burglary, rape, and murder continued.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Several homes were set on fire, and tombstones were shattered.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] British forces found that the majority of illicit weapons were concealed on the bodies of Arab women.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] On Monday evening, all forces were evacuated from the Old City, a step described in the Palin Report as "an error of judgment".
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Even with martial law, it took British authorities another four days to restore order.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The Old City's Jewish community had no training or weapons, and Jabotinsky's men had found themselves outside the walled Old City and were unable to enter it before the British sealed the area off.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Two volunteers were able to enter the Jewish Quarter disguised as medical personnel to organize self-defense – using rocks and boiling water.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Five Jews and four Arabs died in the riots.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Two-hundred and sixteen Jews were injured, 18 critically, and 23 Arabs, one critically.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] About 300 Jews were evacuated from the Old City.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] In Hebrew the incidents were described as *meoraot*, connoting targeted attacks reminiscent of what had often occurred especially in Russia, whereas Palestinian Arabs referred to them as an heroic witness to an 'Arab Revolt'.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The use of the word pogrom to describe such outbreaks of communal violence bore with it the implication that the governing authorities, in this case the British administration, had actively connived in an anti-Jewish riot.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Their assertions were never substantiated, and Meinertzhagen was discharged.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The Zionist Commission noted that before the riots Arab milkmen started to demand their customers in Meah Shearim pay them on the spot, explaining that they would no longer be serving the Jewish neighbourhood.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Christian storekeepers had marked their shops in advance with the sign of the cross so that they would not be mistakenly looted.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] A previous commission report also accused Storrs of inciting the Arabs, blaming him for sabotaging attempts to purchase the Western Wall as well.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] A petition circulated among American citizens and presented to their consul protested that British authorities had prevented Jews from defending themselves.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] After the violence broke out, Ze'ev Jabotinsky met Military Governor Storrs and suggested deployment of his volunteers, but his request was rejected.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Storrs confiscated his pistol and demanded to know the location of his other weapons, threatening to arrest him for possessing a firearm.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Later, Storrs changed his mind and asked for 200 volunteers to report to the police headquarters to be sworn in as deputies.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] After they arrived and the administering of the oath had begun, orders came to cease and he sent them away.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Arab volunteers had also been invited, and were likewise sent away.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] On Sunday night, the first day of the riots, several dozen rioters were arrested, but on Monday morning they were allowed to attend morning prayers and were then released.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] On Monday evening, after martial law was declared, the soldiers were evacuated from the Old City, a step described in the Palin Report as "an error of judgment".
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] After the riots, Storrs visited Menachem Ussishkin, the new head of the Zionist Commission, to express "regrets for the tragedy that has befallen us".
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The Palin Report noted that Jewish representatives persisted in describing the events as a "pogrom", implying that the British administration had connived in the violence.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The Palin Commission (or Palin Court of Inquiry), a committee of inquiry sent to the region in May 1920 by the British authorities, examined the reasons for this trouble.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The Palin Report on the April riots was not signed until July 1920, after the San Remo conference and replacement of the British OETA by a High Commissioner, Sir Herbert Samuel.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The Report was submitted in August 1920, though never published, and was critical of both sides.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The report blamed the Zionists, 'whose impatience to achieve their ultimate goal and indiscretion are largely responsible for this unhappy state of feeling’ and singled out Amin al-Husayni and Ze'ev Jabotinsky in particular.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] However, they incorrectly identified the anti-socialist Jabotinsky as organizer of the "definite Bolshevist" Poalei Zion ('Zionist Workers') party.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The report was critical of some of the actions of OETA military command, particularly the withdrawal of troops from inside Jerusalem early on the morning of Monday, 5 April and that, once martial law had been proclaimed, it was slow to regain control.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Over 200 people were put on trial as a result of the riots, including 39 Jews.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Musa Kazim al-Husayni was replaced as mayor by the head of the rival Nashashibi clan, Ragheb Bey Nashashibi.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Amin al-Husayni and Aref al-Aref were arrested for incitement, but when they were let out on bail they both escaped to Syria.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] In another version, al-Aref was warned and escaped before being arrested.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] In their absence, a military court sentenced them to 10 years imprisonment.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The Arab riots were publicly protested by sheikhs from 82 villages in the Jerusalem and Jaffa areas who issued a formal statement saying that, in their view, Zionist settlement was not a danger to their communities.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Similar declarations would be repeated in cablegrams sent to London in 1922, as hundreds of sheikhs and mukhtars lent their authority and support to Jewish immigration.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The tenor of these positions was that such immigration would, as the Zionist movement itself affirmed, improve the lives of Arabs as industrial development progressed.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The sheikhs protesting the riots, and telegramming later the British colonial secretary to express solidarity with the Zionist programme were sometimes bribed to state this position by the World Zionist Organisation.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] British soldiers were sent to search Jews for arms at the demand of the Palestinian Arab leadership.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] They searched the offices and apartments of Chaim Weizmann, the head of the Zionist Commission, and Jabotinsky.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] At Jabotinsky's house, they found three rifles, two pistols, and 250 rounds of ammunition.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Nineteen men were arrested, but not Jabotinsky, who went to the jail of his own volition to insist on his arrest.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] A military judge released him because he had not been home when the guns were discovered, but he was again arrested a few hours later.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Jabotinsky was convicted of possessing the pistol that Storrs had confiscated on the riot's first day, among other things.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The primary witness was none other than Ronald Storrs, who said he "did not remember" being told about the self-defence organization.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] He was sentenced to 15 years' imprisonment and sent to Egypt, though the next day he was returned to Acre Prison.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Jabotinsky's trial and sentencing created an uproar, and were protested by London press including *The Times* and questioned in the British Parliament.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Even before the editorials appeared, the commander of British forces in Palestine and Egypt, General Congreve, wrote Field Marshal Wilson that Jews were sentenced far more severely than Arabs who had committed worse offences.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] He reduced Jabotinsky's sentence to a year, and that of the other 19 Jews arrested with him to six months.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] The new civilian government under Herbert Samuel granted a general amnesty in early 1921.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] However, Amin al-Husayni and Aref al-Aref were excluded from the amnesty because they had fled before their convictions had been passed down.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Samuel pardoned Amin in March 1921 and appointed him Mufti of Jerusalem.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] When the Supreme Muslim Council was created in the following year, Husayni demanded and received the title Grand Mufti, a position which came with life tenure.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Also, General Storrs became the civil governor of Jerusalem under the new administration.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] As the riots began, Jewish immigration to Palestine was temporarily halted by the British.
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Also, feeling that the British were unwilling to defend Jewish settlements from continuous Arab attacks, Palestinian Jews set up self-defense units, which came to be called the Haganah ("defense").
[src:israel/1920-nebi-musa-riots] Furthermore, the riots increased the feeling of Palestinian nationalism within the Palestinian Arab community.
[src:israel/il] The .il top-level domain is one of the earliest registered ccTLDs.
[src:israel/il] When Israel registered it, on 24 October 1985, it was the third registration of any ccTLD, after .us and .uk, which were registered earlier that year.
[src:israel/il] As of 19 August 2023 there are 285,060 domain names registered under the .il ccTLD in Israel.
[src:israel/il] On 19 May 2020, ICANN approved the use of the `**ישראל.**`‎ domain, that was proposed in 2012.
[src:israel/il] It was delegated on 11 February 2021, and since 22 November 2022 it is possible to register domain names in full Hebrew script.
[src:israel/il] As a more private initiative the top-level domain **.קום** ("com") was registered by VeriSign in 2016.
[src:israel/il] It has as of 2020 many thousand second-level domains, mostly in Hebrew script, some in Latin script.
[src:israel/il] Registration of other second-level domain names directly under .il is not supported.
[src:israel/il] Hebrew third level domains such as `איגוד-האינטרנט.org.il` are available since 2010.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Land of Israel, also called Palestine or the Holy Land, was home to the ancient Canaanites and later the kingdoms of Israel and Judah and Hasmonean Judea.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Located near continental crossroads, its demographics shifted under various empires.
[src:israel/israel-p01] 19th-century European antisemitism fuelled the Zionist movement for a Jewish homeland, which gained British support with the 1917 Balfour Declaration.
[src:israel/israel-p01] After World War I, Britain occupied the region and established Mandatory Palestine.
[src:israel/israel-p01] British rule and Jewish immigration in the leadup to the Holocaust intensified Arab-Jewish tensions, which escalated into a civil war after the 1947 United Nations (UN) Partition Plan.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Israel declared independence as the British Mandate ended on 14 May 1948, followed by an invasion by Arab states.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The 1949 armistice expanded Israel beyond the UN plan, while no new Arab state was created, leaving Gaza under Egyptian control and the West Bank ruled by Jordan.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Most Palestinian Arabs fled or were expelled during the Nakba, while Israeli independence prompted antisemitism in the Arab world and Jewish exodus therefrom, mainly to Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p01] After the 1967 Six-Day War, Israel occupied the West Bank, Gaza and Egyptian Sinai, and annexed East Jerusalem and the Syrian Golan Heights.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Peace treaties were signed with Egypt in 1979 (the Sinai being returned in 1982) and Jordan in 1994.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The 1993 Oslo Accords introduced limited Palestinian self-rule in the West Bank and Gaza, while the 2020 Abraham Accords normalised ties with more Arab states, but the Israeli–Palestinian conflict persists.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Israeli occupation of the Palestinian territories has drawn international criticism, with experts calling its actions war crimes and crimes against humanity.
[src:israel/israel-p01] After the Hamas-led October 7 attacks, Israel began committing genocide against Palestinians in Gaza.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Israel and its allies, including the United States, deny that Israel's actions constitute genocide.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Basic Laws of Israel establish the Knesset as a proportionally elected parliament.
[src:israel/israel-p01] It shapes the government, led by the prime minister, and elects the largely ceremonial president.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Israel has one of the Middle East's largest economies, one of Asia's highest living standards, and globally ranks 25th in nominal GDP and 14th in nominal GDP per capita.
[src:israel/israel-p01] One of the world's most technologically advanced countries, Israel allocates a larger share of its economy to research and development than any other state and is believed to possess nuclear weapons.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The only country with a revived official language, Hebrew, the culture of Israel combines Jewish traditions with Arab influences.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The names Land of Israel and Children of Israel have historically been used to refer to the biblical Kingdom of Israel and the entire Jewish people respectively.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The name *Israel* (Hebrew: *Yīsrāʾēl*; Septuagint Ancient Greek: Ἰσραήλ, *Israēl*, "El (God) persists/rules") refers to the patriarch Jacob who, according to the Hebrew Bible, was given the name after he successfully wrestled with the Angel of the Lord.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The earliest known archaeological artefact to mention the word *Israel* as a collective is the Merneptah Stele of ancient Egypt (dated to the late-13th century BCE).
[src:israel/israel-p01] Under the British Mandate (1920–1948), the entire region was known as *Palestine*.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The name *Israel* was suggested by David Ben-Gurion and passed by a vote of 6–3.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In the early weeks after establishment, the government chose the term *Israeli* to denote a citizen of the state.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Ubeidiya prehistoric site in northern Israel shows the presence of archaic humans around 1.5 million years ago.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The second-oldest evidence of anatomically modern humans outside Africa is a 200,000-year-old fossil from Misliya Cave on Mount Carmel.
[src:israel/israel-p01] 10,000 BCE) may be linked to the Proto-Afroasiatic language and is notable for adopting sedentism before the advent of agriculture and the Neolithic Revolution.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Early references to "Canaan" and "Canaanites" appear in ancient Near Eastern and Egyptian texts (c.
[src:israel/israel-p01] 2000 BCE); these populations were structured as politically independent city-states.
[src:israel/israel-p01] During the Late Bronze Age (1550–1200 BCE), large parts of Canaan formed vassal states of the New Kingdom of Egypt.
[src:israel/israel-p01] As a result of the Late Bronze Age collapse, Canaan fell into chaos, and Egyptian control over the region collapsed.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Ancestors of the Israelites are thought to have included ancient Semitic-speaking peoples native to this area.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Modern archaeological accounts suggest that the Israelites and their culture branched out of the Canaanite peoples through the development of a distinct monolatristic—and later monotheistic—religion centered on Yahweh.
[src:israel/israel-p01] They spoke an archaic form of Hebrew, known as Biblical Hebrew.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Around the same time, the Philistines settled on the southern coastal plain.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Most modern scholars agree that the Exodus narrative in the Torah and Old Testament did not take place as depicted; however, some elements of these traditions do have historical roots.
[src:israel/israel-p01] There is debate about the earliest existence of the Kingdoms of Israel and Judah and their extent and power.
[src:israel/israel-p01] While it is unclear if there was a United Kingdom of Israel, historians and archaeologists agree that the northern Kingdom of Israel existed by ca.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Kingdom of Israel was the more prosperous of the two and soon developed into a regional power, with a capital at Samaria; during the Omride dynasty, it controlled Samaria, Galilee, the upper Jordan Valley, the plain of Sharon and large parts of Transjordan.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Kingdom of Israel was conquered around 720 BCE by the Neo-Assyrian Empire.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Kingdom of Judah, under Davidic rule with its capital in Jerusalem, later became a client state of first the Neo-Assyrian Empire and then the Neo-Babylonian Empire.
[src:israel/israel-p01] It is estimated that the region's population was around 400,000 in the Iron Age II.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 587/6 BCE, following a revolt in Judah, King Nebuchadnezzar II besieged and destroyed Jerusalem and Solomon's Temple, dissolved the kingdom and exiled much of the Judean elite to Babylon.
[src:israel/israel-p01] After capturing Babylon in 539 BCE, Cyrus the Great, founder of the Achaemenid Empire, issued a proclamation allowing the exiled Judean population to return.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The construction of the Second Temple was completed c.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Achaemenids ruled the region as the province of Yehud Medinata.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 332 BCE, Alexander the Great conquered the region as part of his campaign against the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:israel/israel-p01] After his death, the area was controlled by the Ptolemaic and Seleucid empires as a part of Coele-Syria.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Under the Hellenistic kingdoms, ongoing Hellenisation generated cultural tensions among the Jewish population that culminated under Antiochus IV, whose decrees outlawed Jewish practices and triggered the Maccabean Revolt in 167 BCE.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The revolt weakened Seleucid control over Judea; by 142/141 BCE the Hasmoneans had secured autonomy and soon established an independent Jewish kingdom that, in the late 2nd–early 1st century BCE, expanded into neighbouring territories.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Hasmonean civil war ended with the Roman siege of Jerusalem in 63 BCE.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 37 BCE, Herod the Great was installed as a dynastic vassal of Rome following the Roman–Parthian Wars.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 6 CE, the area was annexed as the Roman province of Judaea; tensions with Roman rule led to a series of Jewish–Roman wars, resulting in widespread destruction.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The First Jewish–Roman War (66–73 CE) resulted in the destruction of Jerusalem and the Second Temple and a sizable portion of the population being killed or displaced.
[src:israel/israel-p01] A second uprising known as the Bar Kokhba revolt (132–136 CE) initially allowed the Jews to form an independent state, but the Romans brutally crushed the rebellion, devastating and depopulating Judea's countryside.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Jerusalem was rebuilt as a Roman colony (Aelia Capitolina), and the province of Judea was renamed Syria Palaestina.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Jews were expelled from the districts surrounding Jerusalem.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Nevertheless, there was a continuous small Jewish presence, and Galilee became its religious center.
[src:israel/israel-p01] During the Byzantine period, Early Christianity displaced Roman paganism in the 4th century CE, with Constantine embracing and promoting the Christian religion and Theodosius I making it the state religion.
[src:israel/israel-p01] A series of laws were passed that discriminated against Jews and Judaism, and Jews were persecuted by both the church and the authorities.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Many Jews had emigrated to flourishing diaspora communities, while locally there was both Christian immigration and local conversion.
[src:israel/israel-p01] By the middle of the 5th century, there was a Christian majority.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Towards the end of the 5th century, Samaritan revolts erupted, continuing until the late 6th century and resulting in a large decrease in the Samaritan population.
[src:israel/israel-p01] After the Sasanian conquest of Jerusalem and the short-lived Jewish revolt against Heraclius in 614 CE, the Byzantine Empire reconsolidated control of the area in 628.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 634–641 CE, the Rashidun Caliphate conquered the Levant.
[src:israel/israel-p01] 634–644) lifted the Christian ban on Jews entering Jerusalem and permitted them to worship there.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Over the next six centuries, control of the region transferred between the Umayyad, Abbasid, and Fatimid caliphates, and subsequently the Seljuk and Ayyubid dynasties.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The population drastically decreased during the following several centuries, dropping from an estimated 1 million during Roman and Byzantine periods to about 300,000 by the early Ottoman period, and there was steady Arabisation and Islamisation.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The end of the 11th century brought the Crusades, papally-sanctioned incursions of Christian crusaders intent on wresting Jerusalem and the Holy Land from Muslim control and establishing crusader states.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Ayyubids pushed back the crusaders before Muslim rule was fully restored by the Mamluk sultans of Egypt in 1291.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 1516, the Ottoman Empire conquered the region and ruled it as part of Ottoman Syria.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Two violent incidents took place against Jews, the 1517 Safed attacks and the 1517 Hebron attacks, after the Turkish Ottomans ousted the Mamluks during the Ottoman–Mamluk War.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Under the Ottoman Empire, the Levant was fairly cosmopolitan, with religious freedoms for Christians, Muslims, and Jews.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 1561 the Ottoman sultan invited Sephardic Jews escaping the Spanish Inquisition to settle in and rebuild the city of Tiberias.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Under the Ottoman Empire's millet system, Christians and Jews were considered *dhimmi* ("protected") under Ottoman law in exchange for loyalty to the state and payment of the *jizya* tax.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Non-Muslim Ottoman subjects faced geographic and lifestyle restrictions, though these were not always enforced.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The millet system organised non-Muslims into autonomous communities on the basis of religion.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The concept of an eventual return to Zion remained a symbol within religious Jewish belief which emphasised that their return should be determined by Divine Providence rather than human action.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Jewish population of Palestine from the Ottoman rule to the beginning of the Zionist movement, known as the Old Yishuv, comprised a minority and fluctuated in size.
[src:israel/israel-p01] During the 16th century, Jewish communities struck roots in the Four Holy Cities—Jerusalem, Tiberias, Hebron, and Safed—and in 1697, Rabbi Yehuda Hachasid led 1,500 Jews to Jerusalem.
[src:israel/israel-p01] A 1660 Druze revolt against the Ottomans destroyed Safed and Tiberias.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In the second half of the 18th century, Eastern European Jews who were opponents of Hasidism, known as the Perushim, settled in Palestine.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In the late 18th century, local Arab Sheikh Daher al-Umar created a de facto independent emirate in the Galilee.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Ottoman attempts to subdue the sheikh failed.
[src:israel/israel-p01] After Daher's death the Ottomans regained control of the area.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 1799, governor Jazzar Pasha repelled an assault on Acre by Napoleon's troops, prompting the French to abandon the Syrian campaign.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 1834, a revolt by Palestinian Arab peasants against Egyptian conscription and taxation policies under Muhammad Ali was suppressed; Muhammad Ali's army retreated and Ottoman rule was restored with British support in 1840.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Tanzimat reforms were implemented across the Ottoman Empire.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The first wave of modern Jewish migration to Ottoman-ruled Palestine, known as the First Aliyah, began in 1881, as Jews fled pogroms in Eastern Europe.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The 1882 May Laws increased economic discrimination against Jews, and restricted where they could live.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Antisemitism, pogroms and official policies in tsarist Russia led to the emigration of three million Jews in the years between 1882 and 1914, only 1% of whom went to Palestine.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Those who went to Palestine were driven primarily by ideas of self-determination and Jewish identity, rather than as a response to pogroms or economic insecurity.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Zionism emerged during this time as a political movement to reestablish a Jewish homeland in Palestine.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The revival of the Hebrew language, during which Hebrew was adapted for modern use and gradually became the primary language of Jews in Palestine, also began.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Second Aliyah (1904–1914) began after the Kishinev pogrom; some 40,000 Jews settled in Palestine, although nearly half left eventually.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Both the first and second waves of migrants were mainly Orthodox Jews.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Second Aliyah included Zionist socialist groups who established the *kibbutz* movement based on the idea of establishing a separate Jewish economy based exclusively on Jewish labour.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Those of the Second Aliyah who became leaders of the Yishuv in the coming decades believed that the Jewish settler economy should not depend on Arab labour.
[src:israel/israel-p01] This would be a dominant source of antagonism with the Arab population, with the new Yishuv's nationalist ideology overpowering its socialist one.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Though the immigrants of the Second Aliyah largely sought to create communal Jewish agricultural settlements, Tel Aviv was established as the first planned Jewish town in 1909.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Jewish armed militias emerged during this period, the first being Bar-Giora in 1907.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Two years later, the larger Hashomer organisation was founded as its replacement.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Chaim Weizmann's efforts to garner British support for the Zionist movement eventually secured the Balfour Declaration of 1917, stating Britain's support for the creation of a Jewish "national home" in Palestine.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Weizmann's interpretation of the declaration was that negotiations on the future of the country were to happen directly between Britain and the Jews, excluding Arabs.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Jewish-Arab relations in Palestine deteriorated dramatically in the following years.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 1918, the Jewish Legion, primarily Zionist volunteers, assisted in the British conquest of Palestine.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 1920, the territory was divided between Britain and France under the mandate system, and the British-administered area (including modern Israel) was named Mandatory Palestine.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Arab opposition to British rule and Jewish immigration led to the 1920 Palestine riots and the formation of a Jewish militia known as the Haganah as an outgrowth of Hashomer, from which the Irgun and Lehi paramilitaries later split.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 1922, the League of Nations granted Britain the Mandate for Palestine under terms which included the Balfour Declaration with its promise to the Jews and with similar provisions regarding the Arab Palestinians.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The population of the area was predominantly Arab and Muslim, with Jews accounting for about 11% and Arab Christians about 9.5% of the population.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The rise of Nazism and the increasing persecution of Jews in 1930s Europe led to the Fifth Aliyah, with an influx of a quarter of a million Jews.
[src:israel/israel-p01] This was a major cause of the Arab revolt of 1936–39, which was suppressed by British security forces and Zionist militias.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Several hundred British security personnel and Jews were killed; 5,032 Arabs were killed, 14,760 wounded, and 12,622 detained.
[src:israel/israel-p01] An estimated ten per cent of the adult male Palestinian Arab population was killed, wounded, imprisoned, or exiled.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The British introduced restrictions on Jewish immigration to Palestine with the White Paper of 1939.
[src:israel/israel-p01] With countries around the world turning away Jewish refugees fleeing the Holocaust, a clandestine movement known as Aliyah Bet was organised to bring Jews to Palestine.
[src:israel/israel-p01] During World War II, Palestine was repeatedly bombed by Axis aircraft, causing casualties among both Jews and Arabs.
[src:israel/israel-p01] About 30,000 Jews from Palestine served in the British military during the war, of whom around 700 were killed.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Some 12,000 Palestinian Arabs also served in the British military during the war.
[src:israel/israel-p01] At the end of the war, about 31% of the population of Palestine was Jewish.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The UK found itself facing a Jewish insurgency over immigration restrictions from 1944, which intensified following the end of the war, and continued conflict with the Arab community over limit levels.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Haganah joined Irgun and Lehi in an armed struggle against British rule.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Haganah attempted to bring tens of thousands of Jewish refugees and Holocaust survivors to Palestine by ship.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Most of the ships were intercepted by the Royal Navy and the refugees placed in detention camps in Atlit and Cyprus.
[src:israel/israel-p01] On 22 July 1946, Irgun bombed the British administrative headquarters for Palestine, killing 91.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The attack was a response to Operation Agatha (a series of raids, including one on the Jewish Agency, by the British) and was the deadliest directed at the British during the Mandate era.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Jewish insurgency continued throughout 1946 and 1947 despite concerted efforts by the British military and Palestine Police Force to suppress it.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In February 1947, the British referred the Palestine issue to the newly formed United Nations.
[src:israel/israel-p01] On 15 May 1947, the UN General Assembly resolved that a Special Committee be created "to prepare ... a report on the question of Palestine".
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Report of the Committee proposed a plan to replace the British Mandate with "an independent Arab State, an independent Jewish State, and the City of Jerusalem [...] the last to be under an International Trusteeship System".
[src:israel/israel-p01] Meanwhile, the Jewish insurgency continued and peaked in July 1947, with a series of widespread guerrilla raids culminating in the Sergeants affair, in which the Irgun took two British sergeants hostage as attempted leverage against the planned execution of three Irgun operatives.
[src:israel/israel-p01] After the executions were carried out, the Irgun killed the two British soldiers, hanged their bodies from trees, and left a booby trap at the scene which injured a British soldier.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The incident caused widespread outrage in the UK.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In September 1947, the British cabinet decided to evacuate Palestine as the Mandate was no longer tenable.
[src:israel/israel-p01] On 29 November 1947, the General Assembly adopted Resolution 181 (II).
[src:israel/israel-p01] The plan attached to the resolution was essentially that proposed in the report of 3 September.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Jewish Agency, the recognised representative of the Jewish community, accepted the plan, which assigned 55–56% of Mandatory Palestine to the Jews.
[src:israel/israel-p01] At the time, the Jews were about a third of the population and owned around 6–7% of the land.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Arabs constituted the majority and owned about 20% of the land, with the remainder held by the Mandate authorities or foreign landowners.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Arab League and Arab Higher Committee of Palestine rejected the partition plan on the basis that the partition plan privileged European interests over those of the Palestinians, and indicated that they would reject any other plan of partition.
[src:israel/israel-p01] On 1 December 1947, the Arab Higher Committee proclaimed a three-day strike, and riots broke out in Jerusalem.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The situation spiralled into a civil war.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Colonial Secretary Arthur Creech Jones announced that the British Mandate would end on 15 May 1948, at which point the British would evacuate.
[src:israel/israel-p01] As Arab militias and gangs attacked Jewish areas, they were faced mainly by the Haganah as well as the smaller Irgun and Lehi.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In April 1948, the Haganah moved onto the offensive.
[src:israel/israel-p01] On 14 May 1948, the day before the expiration of the British Mandate, David Ben-Gurion, the head of the Jewish Agency, declared "the establishment of a Jewish state in Eretz-Israel".
[src:israel/israel-p01] The following day, the armies of four Arab countries—Egypt, Syria, Transjordan, and Iraq—entered what had been Mandatory Palestine, launching the 1948 Arab–Israeli War; contingents from Yemen, Morocco, Saudi Arabia, and Sudan joined the war.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The purpose of the invasion was to prevent the establishment of the Jewish state.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Arab League stated the invasion was to restore order and prevent further bloodshed.
[src:israel/israel-p01] After a year of fighting, a ceasefire was declared and temporary borders, known as the Green Line, were established.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Jordan annexed what became known as the West Bank, including East Jerusalem, and Egypt occupied the Gaza Strip.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Over 700,000 Palestinians fled or were expelled by Zionist militias and the Israeli military—what would become known in Arabic as the *Nakba* ('catastrophe').
[src:israel/israel-p01] The events also led to the destruction of most of Palestine's Arab culture, identity, and national aspirations.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Some 156,000 Arabs remained and became Arab citizens of Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p01] By United Nations General Assembly Resolution 273, Israel was admitted as a member of the UN on 11 May 1949.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In the early years of the state, the Labour Zionist movement led by Prime Minister Ben-Gurion dominated Israeli politics.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Immigration to Israel during the late 1940s and early 1950s was aided by the Israeli Immigration Department and the non-government sponsored Mossad LeAliyah Bet (lit.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The latter engaged in clandestine operations in countries, particularly in the Middle East and Eastern Europe, where the lives of Jews were in danger and exit was difficult.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Mossad LeAliyah Bet was disbanded in 1953.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The immigration was in accordance with the One Million Plan.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Some immigrants held Zionist beliefs or came for the promise of a better life, while others moved to escape persecution or were expelled from their homes.
[src:israel/israel-p01] An influx of Holocaust survivors and Jews from Arab and Muslim countries to Israel during the first three years increased the number of Jews from 700,000 to 1,400,000.
[src:israel/israel-p01] By 1958, the population had risen to two million.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Between 1948 and 1970, approximately 1,150,000 Jewish refugees relocated to Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Some immigrants arrived as refugees and were housed in temporary camps known as *ma'abarot*; by 1952, over 200,000 people were living in these tent cities.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Jews of European background were often treated more favourably than Jews from Middle Eastern and North African countries—housing units reserved for the latter were often re-designated for the former, so Jews newly arrived from Arab lands generally ended up staying longer in transit camps.
[src:israel/israel-p01] During this period, food, clothes and furniture were rationed in what became known as the austerity period.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The need to solve the crisis led Ben-Gurion to sign a reparations agreement with West Germany that triggered mass protests by Jews angered at the idea that Israel could accept monetary compensation for the Holocaust.
[src:israel/israel-p01] There were further expulsions of Palestinians after the establishment of Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p01] During the 1950s, Israel was frequently attacked by Palestinian fedayeen, nearly always against civilians, mainly from the Egyptian-occupied Gaza Strip, leading to several Israeli reprisal operations.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 1956, the UK and France aimed at regaining control of the Suez Canal, which Egypt had nationalised.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The continued blockade of the Suez Canal and Straits of Tiran to Israeli shipping, together with increasing fedayeen attacks against Israel's southern population and recent Arab threatening statements, prompted Israel to attack Egypt.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Israel joined a secret alliance with the UK and France and overran the Sinai Peninsula in the Suez Crisis but was pressured to withdraw by the UN in return for guarantees of Israeli shipping rights.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The war resulted in significant reduction of Israeli border infiltration.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In the early 1960s, Israel captured Nazi war criminal Adolf Eichmann in Argentina and brought him to Israel for trial.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Eichmann remains the only person executed in Israel by conviction in an Israeli civilian court.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 1963, Israel was engaged in a diplomatic standoff with the United States in relation to the Israeli nuclear programme.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Since 1964 Arab countries, concerned over Israeli plans to divert waters of the Jordan River into the coastal plain, had been trying to divert the headwaters to deprive Israel of water resources, provoking tensions between Israel on the one hand, and Syria and Lebanon on the other.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Arab nationalists led by Egyptian President Gamal Abdel Nasser refused to recognise Israel and called for its destruction.
[src:israel/israel-p01] By 1966, Israeli-Arab relations had deteriorated to the point of battles taking place between Israeli and Arab forces.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In May 1967, Egypt massed its army near the border with Israel, expelled UN peacekeepers stationed in the Sinai Peninsula since 1957, and blocked Israel's access to the Red Sea.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Other Arab states mobilised their forces.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Israel reiterated that these actions were a *casus belli* and launched a pre-emptive strike (Operation Focus) against Egypt in June.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In the ensuing Six-Day War, Israel captured and occupied the West Bank from Jordan, the Gaza Strip and Sinai Peninsula from Egypt, and the Golan Heights from Syria.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Israeli forces expelled ~300,000 Palestinians from the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Jerusalem's boundaries were enlarged, incorporating East Jerusalem.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The 1949 Green Line became the administrative boundary between Israel and the occupied territories.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Following the 1967 war and the "Three Nos" resolution of the Arab League, Israel faced attacks from the Egyptians in the Sinai Peninsula during the 1967–1970 War of Attrition, and from Palestinian groups targeting Israelis in the occupied territories, globally, and in Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Most important among the Palestinian and Arab groups was the Palestine Liberation Organisation (PLO), established in 1964, which initially committed itself to "armed struggle as the only way to liberate the homeland".
[src:israel/israel-p01] In the late 1960s and early 1970s, Palestinian groups launched attacks against Israeli and Jewish targets around the world, including a massacre of Israeli athletes at the 1972 Summer Olympics in Munich.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Israeli government responded with an assassination campaign against the organisers of the massacre, a bombing and a raid on the PLO headquarters in Lebanon.
[src:israel/israel-p01] On 6 October 1973, the Egyptian and Syrian armies launched a surprise attack against Israeli forces in the Sinai Peninsula and Golan Heights, opening the Yom Kippur War.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The war ended on 25 October with Israel repelling Egyptian and Syrian forces but suffering great losses.
[src:israel/israel-p01] An internal inquiry exonerated the government of responsibility for failures before and during the war, but public anger forced Prime Minister Golda Meir to resign.
[src:israel/israel-p01] On 27 June 1976, Air France Flight 139 was hijacked in flight from Israel to France by Palestinian guerrillas; Israeli commandos rescued 102 of 106 Israeli hostages days later.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The 1977 Knesset elections marked a major turning point in Israeli political history as Menachem Begin's Likud party took control from the Labor Party.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Later that year, Egyptian President Anwar El Sadat made a trip to Israel and spoke before the Knesset in what was the first recognition of Israel by an Arab head of state.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Sadat and Begin signed the Camp David Accords (1978) and the Egypt–Israel peace treaty (1979).
[src:israel/israel-p01] In return, Israel withdrew from the Sinai Peninsula and agreed to enter negotiations over autonomy for Palestinians in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
[src:israel/israel-p01] On 11 March 1978, a PLO guerilla raid from Lebanon led to the Coastal Road massacre.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Israel responded by launching an invasion of southern Lebanon to destroy PLO bases.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Begin's government meanwhile provided incentives for Israelis to settle in the occupied West Bank, increasing friction with the Palestinians there.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The 1980 Jerusalem Law was believed by some to reaffirm Israel's 1967 annexation of Jerusalem by government decree and reignited international controversy over the status of the city.
[src:israel/israel-p01] No Israeli legislation has defined the territory of Israel, and no act specifically included East Jerusalem therein.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 1981 Israel effectively annexed the Golan Heights.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The international community largely rejected these moves, with the UN Security Council declaring both the Jerusalem Law and the Golan Heights Law null and void.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Several waves of Ethiopian Jews immigrated to Israel since the 1980s, while between 1990 and 1994, immigration from the post-Soviet states increased Israel's population by twelve per cent.
[src:israel/israel-p01] On 7 June 1981, during the Iran–Iraq War, the Israeli air force destroyed Iraq's sole nuclear reactor, then under construction, in order to impede the Iraqi nuclear weapons programme.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Following a series of PLO attacks in 1982, Israel invaded Lebanon to destroy the PLO bases.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In the first six days, Israel destroyed the military forces of the PLO in Lebanon and decisively defeated the Syrians.
[src:israel/israel-p01] An Israeli government inquiry (the Kahan Commission) held Begin and several Israeli generals indirectly responsible for the Sabra and Shatila massacre and held defence minister Ariel Sharon as bearing "personal responsibility".
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 1985, Israel responded to a Palestinian terrorist attack in Cyprus by bombing the PLO headquarters in Tunisia.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Israel withdrew from most of Lebanon in 1986 but continued to occupy a borderland buffer zone in southern Lebanon until 2000, from where Israeli forces engaged in conflict with Hezbollah.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The First Intifada, a Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule, broke out in 1987, with waves of uncoordinated demonstrations and violence in the occupied West Bank and Gaza.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Over the following six years, the intifada became more organised and included economic and cultural measures aimed at disrupting the Israeli occupation.
[src:israel/israel-p01] During the 1991 Gulf War, the PLO supported Saddam Hussein and Iraqi missile attacks against Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Despite public outrage, Israel heeded American calls to refrain from hitting back.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 1992, Yitzhak Rabin became prime minister following an election in which his party called for compromise with Israel's neighbours.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The following year, Shimon Peres on behalf of Israel and Yasser Arafat for the PLO signed the Oslo Accords, which gave the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) the right to govern parts of the West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The PLO also recognised Israel's right to exist and pledged an end to terrorism.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 1994, the Israel–Jordan peace treaty was signed, making Jordan the second Arab country to normalise relations with Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Arab public support for the Accords was damaged by the continuation of Israeli settlements and checkpoints, and the deterioration of economic conditions.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Israeli public support for the Accords waned after Palestinian suicide attacks.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In November 1995, Rabin was assassinated by Yigal Amir, a far-right Jew who opposed the Accords.
[src:israel/israel-p01] During Benjamin Netanyahu's premiership at the end of the 1990s, Israel agreed to withdraw from Hebron, though this was never ratified or implemented, and he signed the Wye River Memorandum.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The agreement dealt with further redeployments in the West Bank and security issues.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The memorandum was criticised by major international human rights organisations for its "encouragement" of human rights abuses.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Ehud Barak, elected prime minister in 1999, withdrew forces from southern Lebanon and conducted negotiations with PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat and U.S.
[src:israel/israel-p01] President Bill Clinton at the 2000 Camp David Summit.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Barak offered a plan for the establishment of a Palestinian state, including the entirety of the Gaza Strip and over 90% of the West Bank with Jerusalem as a shared capital.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Each side blamed the other for the failure of the talks.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In late 2000, after a controversial visit by Sharon to the Temple Mount, the Second Intifada began.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The popular uprising faced disproportionate repression from the Israeli state.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Palestinian suicide bombings eventually developed into a recurrent feature of the intifada.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Some commentators contend that the intifada was pre-planned by Arafat after the collapse of peace talks.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Sharon became prime minister in a 2001 election; he carried out his plan to unilaterally withdraw from the Gaza Strip and spearheaded the construction of the West Bank barrier, ending the intifada.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Between 2000 and 2008, 1,063 Israelis, 5,517 Palestinians and 64 foreign citizens were killed.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In July 2006, a Hezbollah artillery assault on Israel's northern border communities and a cross-border abduction of two Israeli soldiers precipitated the month-long Second Lebanon War, including an Israeli invasion of Lebanon.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The war wound down in August 2006 after the passage of United Nations Security Council Resolution 1701; Israeli forces mostly withdrew from Lebanon by October 2006 but continued to occupy the Lebanese portion of Ghajar village.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 2007 the Israeli Air Force destroyed a nuclear reactor in Syria.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In 2008, a ceasefire between Hamas and Israel collapsed, resulting in the three-week Gaza War.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In what Israel described as a response to over a hundred Palestinian rocket attacks on southern Israeli cities, Israel began an operation in the Gaza Strip in 2012, lasting eight days.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Israel started another operation in Gaza following an escalation of rocket attacks by Hamas in July 2014.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In May 2021, another round of fighting took place in Gaza and Israel, lasting eleven days.
[src:israel/israel-p01] By the 2010s, increasing regional cooperation between Israel and Arab League countries have been established, culminating in the signing of the Abraham Accords.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Israeli security situation shifted from the traditional Arab–Israeli conflict towards the Iran–Israel proxy conflict and direct confrontation with Iran during the Syrian civil war.
[src:israel/israel-p01] On 7 October 2023, Palestinian militant groups from Gaza, led by Hamas, launched a series of coordinated attacks on Israel, leading to the start of the Gaza war.
[src:israel/israel-p01] On that day, approximately 1,300 Israelis, predominantly civilians, were killed in communities near the Gaza Strip border and during a music festival.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Over 200 hostages were kidnapped and taken to the Gaza Strip.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Studies modeling trauma exposure and assessing mental health outcomes estimated that approximately 5.3% of Israelis may develop PTSD, with national data showing that probable PTSD nearly doubled from 16.2% to 29.8% and rates of anxiety and depression also rising sharply.
[src:israel/israel-p01] After clearing militants from its territory, Israel launched one of the most destructive bombing campaigns in modern history and invaded Gaza on 27 October with the stated objectives of destroying Hamas and freeing hostages.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The fifth war of the Gaza–Israel conflict since 2008, it has been the deadliest for Palestinians in the entire Israeli–Palestinian conflict and the most significant military engagement in the region since the Yom Kippur War in 1973.
[src:israel/israel-p01] A United Nations Special Committee, multiple governments, and various experts and human rights organisations have concluded that Israel is committing genocide against the Palestinian people due to the harm and loss of life inflicted on civilians during the Gaza War.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In April 2024, Israel initiated a wave of airstrikes on Iran, after Iranian strikes targeted Israel, marking the 2024 Iran–Israel conflict the first time in which the two countries have ever directly exchanged fire.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In October 2024, Israel invaded Lebanon and exchanged missile barrages with Iran three weeks later, in response of Iranian strikes earlier in that month.
[src:israel/israel-p01] After nearly a year of the Israel–Hezbollah conflict from October 2023 due to Hezbollah shooting rockets at Israel to support Hamas in Gaza, Israel assassinated Hezbollah secretary general Hassan Nasrallah in September 2024.
[src:israel/israel-p01] A November 2024 ceasefire agreement instructed Israel to withdraw from Lebanon, which Israel mostly did by February 2025, but against the agreement, Israeli forces stayed in five military outposts on highlands in Southern Lebanon.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In June 2025, Israel launched a renewed series of airstrikes on Iran, targeting Iran's air defence systems, missile launchers, their military leadership, and their nuclear programme, which escalated into a full-scale war.
[src:israel/israel-p01] In February 2026, Israel and the United States launched extensive airstrikes on Iran, assassinating Iranian Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei and sparking the 2026 Iran war and the 2026 Lebanon war.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The strikes aimed to destroy the Iranian military, nuclear programme, and achieve regime change.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Israel is located in the Levant area of the Fertile Crescent.
[src:israel/israel-p01] At the eastern end of the Mediterranean Sea, it is bounded by Lebanon to the north, Syria to the north-east, Jordan and the West Bank to the east, and Egypt and the Gaza Strip to the south-west.
[src:israel/israel-p01] It lies between latitudes 29° and 34° N, and longitudes 34° and 36° E.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The sovereign territory of Israel (according to the demarcation lines of the 1949 Armistice Agreements and excluding all territories captured by Israel during the 1967 Six-Day War) is approximately 20,770 square kilometres (8,019 sq mi), of which two per cent is water.
[src:israel/israel-p01] However Israel is so narrow (100 km at its widest, compared to 400 km from north to south) that the exclusive economic zone in the Mediterranean is double the land area of the country.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Despite its small size, Israel is home to a variety of geographic features, from the Negev desert in the south to the inland fertile Jezreel Valley, with mountain ranges of the Galilee, Carmel and towards the Golan in the north.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Israeli coastal plain on the shores of the Mediterranean is home to most of the population.
[src:israel/israel-p01] East of the central highlands lies the Jordan Rift Valley, a small part of the 6,500-kilometre (4,039 mi) Great Rift Valley.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Jordan River runs along the Jordan Rift Valley, from Mount Hermon through the Hulah Valley and the Sea of Galilee to the Dead Sea, the lowest point on the surface of the Earth.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Further south is the Arabah, ending with the Gulf of Eilat, part of the Red Sea.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Makhtesh, or "erosion cirques" are unique to the Negev and the Sinai Peninsula, the largest being the Makhtesh Ramon at 38 km in length.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Forests accounted for 8.5% of the area in 2016, up from 2% in 1948, as the result of a large-scale forest planting programme by the Jewish National Fund.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Jordan Rift Valley is the result of tectonic movements within the Dead Sea Transform (DST) fault system.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The DST forms the transform boundary between the African Plate to the west and the Arabian Plate to the east.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Golan Heights and all of Jordan are part of the Arabian Plate, while the Galilee, West Bank, Coastal Plain, and Negev along with the Sinai Peninsula are on the African Plate.
[src:israel/israel-p01] This tectonic disposition leads to a relatively high seismic activity.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The entire Jordan Valley segment is thought to have ruptured repeatedly, for instance during the last two major earthquakes along this structure in 749 and 1033.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The deficit in slip that has built up since 1033 is sufficient to cause an earthquake of Mw~7.4.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The most catastrophic known earthquakes occurred in 31 BCE, 363, 749, and 1033 CE, that is every ca.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Destructive earthquakes strike about every 80 years, leading to serious loss of life .
[src:israel/israel-p01] While stringent construction regulations are in place and recently built structures are earthquake resistant, as of 2007 many public buildings as well as 50,000 residential buildings did not meet the new standards and were "expected to collapse" if exposed to a strong earthquake.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Temperatures vary widely, especially during the winter.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Coastal areas, such as those of Tel Aviv and Haifa, have a typical Mediterranean climate with cool, rainy winters and long, hot summers.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The area of Beersheba and the northern Negev have a semi-arid climate with hot summers, cool winters, and fewer rainy days.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The southern Negev and the Arabah areas have a desert climate with very hot, dry summers, and mild winters with few days of rain.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The highest temperature of 54 °C (129 °F) was recorded in 1942 in the Tirat Zvi kibbutz.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Mountainous regions can be windy and cold, and areas at elevation of 750 metres (2,460 ft) or more (same elevation as Jerusalem) usually receive at least one snowfall each year.
[src:israel/israel-p01] There are four different phytogeographic regions, due to its location between the temperate and tropical zones.
[src:israel/israel-p01] For this reason, the flora and fauna are extremely diverse.
[src:israel/israel-p01] There are 2,867 known species of plants in Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p01] Of these, at least 253 species are introduced and non-native.
[src:israel/israel-p01] With scarce water resources, Israel has developed various water-saving technologies, including drip irrigation.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The considerable sunlight available for solar energy makes Israel the leading nation in solar energy use per capita—practically every house uses solar panels for water heating.
[src:israel/israel-p01] The Ministry of Environmental Protection has reported that climate change "will have a decisive impact on all areas of life", particularly for vulnerable populations.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel has a parliamentary system, proportional representation and universal suffrage.
[src:israel/israel-p02] A member of parliament supported by a parliamentary majority becomes the prime minister—usually this is the chair of the largest party.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The prime minister is the head of government and of cabinet.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The president is head of state, with largely ceremonial duties.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel is governed by a 120-member parliament, known as the Knesset.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Membership of the Knesset is based on proportional representation of political parties, with a 3.25% electoral threshold, which in practice has resulted in coalition governments.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Residents of Israeli settlements in the West Bank are eligible to vote, and after the 2015 election, 10 of the 120 members of the Knesset (8%) were settlers.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Parliamentary elections are scheduled every four years, but unstable coalitions or a no-confidence vote can dissolve a government earlier.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The first Arab-led party was established in 1988, and as of 2022, Arab-led parties hold about 10% of seats.
[src:israel/israel-p02] A party cannot run for election to the Knesset if its objectives or actions include the "negation of the existence of the State of Israel as the state of the Jewish people".
[src:israel/israel-p02] The Basic Laws of Israel function as an uncodified constitution.
[src:israel/israel-p02] These define Israel as a Jewish and democratic state and the nation-state of exclusively the Jewish people.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In 2003, the Knesset began to draft an official constitution based on these laws.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel has no official religion, but the definition of the state as "Jewish and democratic" creates a strong connection with Judaism.
[src:israel/israel-p02] On 19 July 2018, the Knesset passed a Basic Law that characterises Israel as principally a "Nation State of the Jewish People" and Hebrew as its official language.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The bill ascribes an undefined "special status" to the Arabic language.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The same bill gives Jews a unique right to national self-determination and views the developing of Jewish settlement in the country as "a national interest", empowering the government to "take steps to encourage, advance and implement this interest".
[src:israel/israel-p02] The State of Israel is divided into six main administrative districts, known as *mehozot* (Hebrew: מחוזות; sing.: *mahoz*)—Center, Haifa, Jerusalem, North, South, and Tel Aviv, as well as the Judea and Samaria Area in the West Bank.
[src:israel/israel-p02] All of the Judea and Samaria Area and parts of the Jerusalem and Northern districts are not recognised internationally as part of Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Districts are divided into 15 sub-districts known as *nafot* (Hebrew: נפות; sing.: *nafa*), which are partitioned into 50 natural regions.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The 1950 Law of Return grants Jews the unrestricted right to immigrate to Israel and obtain Israeli citizenship.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Individuals born within the country receive birthright citizenship if at least one parent is a citizen.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israeli law defines Jewish nationality as distinct from Israeli nationality, and the Supreme Court of Israel has ruled that an Israeli nationality does not exist.
[src:israel/israel-p02] A Jewish national is defined as any person practicing Judaism and their descendants.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In 1967, as a result of the Six-Day War, Israel captured and occupied the West Bank (including East Jerusalem), the Gaza Strip and the Golan Heights.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel also captured the Sinai Peninsula but returned it to Egypt as part of the 1979 Egypt–Israel peace treaty.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Between 1982 and 2000, Israel occupied part of southern Lebanon, in what was known as the Security Belt.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Since capture of these territories, Israeli settlements and military installations have been built within each of them, except Lebanon.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The Golan Heights and East Jerusalem have been fully incorporated under Israeli law but not under international law.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel has applied civilian law to both areas and granted their inhabitants permanent residency status and the ability to apply for citizenship.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The UN Security Council has declared the annexation of the Golan Heights and East Jerusalem to be "null and void" and continues to view the territories as occupied.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The status of East Jerusalem in any future peace settlement has at times been a difficult issue in negotiations between Israeli governments and representatives of the Palestinians.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The land is not considered part of Israel under Israeli law, as Israel has consciously refrained from annexing the territory, without ever relinquishing its legal claim to the land or defining a border.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israeli political opposition to annexation primarily stems from the perceived "demographic threat" of incorporating the West Bank's Palestinian population into Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Outside of the Israeli settlements, the West Bank remains under direct Israeli military rule, and Palestinians in the area cannot become Israeli citizens.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The international community maintains that Israel does not have sovereignty in the West Bank and considers Israel's control of the area to be the longest military occupation in modern history.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The West Bank was occupied and annexed by Jordan in 1950, following the 1949 Armistice Agreements.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Only Britain recognised this annexation, and Jordan has since ceded its claim to the territory to the PLO.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The population is mainly Palestinians, including refugees of the 1948 Arab–Israeli War.
[src:israel/israel-p02] From their occupation in 1967 until 1993, the Palestinians living in these territories were under Israeli military administration.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The Gaza Strip is considered to be a "foreign territory" under Israeli law.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel and Egypt operate a land, air, and sea blockade of the Gaza Strip.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The Gaza Strip was occupied by Israel after 1967.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In 2005, as part of a unilateral disengagement plan, Israel removed its settlers and forces from the territory but continues to maintain control of its airspace and waters.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The international community, including numerous international humanitarian organisations and UN bodies, consider Gaza to remain occupied.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Following the 2007 Battle of Gaza, when Hamas assumed power in the Gaza Strip, Israel tightened control of the Gaza crossings along its border, as well as by sea and air, and prevented persons from entering and exiting except for isolated cases it deemed humanitarian.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Gaza has a border with Egypt, and an agreement between Israel, the EU, and the PA governs how border crossings take place.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The application of democracy to its Palestinian citizens and the selective application of Israeli democracy in the Israeli-controlled Palestinian territories have been criticised.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel has been criticised for engaging in systematic and widespread violations of human rights in the occupied territories, including occupation and war crimes against civilians.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The allegations include violations of international humanitarian law by the UN Human Rights Council.
[src:israel/israel-p02] State Department has called reports of abuses of significant human rights of Palestinians "credible" both within Israel and the occupied territories.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Amnesty International and other NGOs have documented mass arbitrary arrests, torture, unlawful killings, systemic abuses and impunity in tandem with a denial of the right to Palestinian self-determination.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Prime Minister Netanyahu has defended the country's security forces for protecting the innocent from terrorists and expressed contempt for what he describes as a lack of concern about the human rights violations committed by "criminal killers".
[src:israel/israel-p02] The international community widely regards Israeli settlements in the occupied territories illegal under international law.
[src:israel/israel-p02] United Nations Security Council Resolution 2334 (passed 2016) states that Israel's settlement activity constitutes a "flagrant violation" of international law and demands that Israel stop such activity and fulfill its obligations as an occupying power under the Fourth Geneva Convention.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In a 2024 advisory opinion, the International Court of Justice stated that occupation of the Palestinian territories violated international law; Israel should end its occupation as quickly as possible and pay reparations.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In addition, the court found that Israel was in breach of article 3 of the International Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Racial Discrimination, which requires states to prevent, prohibit and eradicate all practices of racial segregation and apartheid.
[src:israel/israel-p02] *The Washington Post'*s 2021 survey of scholars and academic experts on the Middle East found an increase from 59% to 65% of these scholars describing Israel as a "one-state reality akin to apartheid".
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israeli human rights organisation Yesh Din has also accused Israel of apartheid.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Amnesty's claim was criticised by politicians and representatives from Israel and its closest allies such as, the US, the UK, the European Commission, Australia, Netherlands and Germany, while said accusations were welcomed by Palestinians and the Arab League.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In 2022, Michael Lynk, a Canadian law professor appointed by the U.N.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Human Rights Council said that the situation met the legal definition of apartheid, and concluded: "Israel has imposed upon Palestine an apartheid reality in a post-apartheid world".
[src:israel/israel-p02] Subsequent reports from his successor, Francesca Albanese and from Permanent United Nations Fact Finding Mission on the Israel Palestine conflict chair Navi Pillay echoed the opinion.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In February 2024, the ICJ held public hearings in regards to the legal consequences arising from the policies and practices of Israel in the occupied Palestinian territory including East Jerusalem.
[src:israel/israel-p02] During the hearings, 24 states and three international organisations said that Israeli practices amount to a breach of the prohibition of apartheid and/or amount to prohibited acts of racial discrimination.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The opinion is silent as to whether the discrimination amounts to apartheid; individual judges were split on the question.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel maintains diplomatic relations with 165 UN member states, the Holy See, Kosovo, the Cook Islands and Niue.
[src:israel/israel-p02] It has 107 diplomatic missions; countries with which it has no diplomatic relations include most Muslim countries.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Six out of 22 nations in the Arab League have normalised relations with Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel remains formally in a state of war with Syria, dating back uninterrupted to 1948.
[src:israel/israel-p02] It has been in a similarly formal state of war with Lebanon since the end of the Lebanese Civil War in 2000, with the Israel–Lebanon border remaining unagreed by treaty.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Despite the peace treaty between Israel and Egypt, Israel is still widely considered an enemy country among Egyptians.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Iran withdrew its recognition of Israel during the Islamic Revolution.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israeli citizens may not visit Syria, Lebanon, Iraq, Saudi Arabia, and Yemen without permission from the Ministry of the Interior.
[src:israel/israel-p02] As a result of the 2008–09 Gaza War, Mauritania, Qatar, Bolivia, and Venezuela suspended political and economic ties with Israel, though Bolivia renewed ties in 2019.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The United States and the Soviet Union were the first two countries to recognise the State of Israel, having declared recognition roughly simultaneously.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Diplomatic relations with the Soviet Union were broken in 1967 following the Six-Day War and renewed in 1991.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The United States regards Israel as its "most reliable partner in the Middle East", based on "common democratic values, religious affinities, and security interests".
[src:israel/israel-p02] The US has provided $68 billion in military assistance and $32 billion in grants to Israel since 1967, under the Foreign Assistance Act (period beginning 1962), more than any other country for that period until 2003.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Most surveyed Americans have held consistently favourable views of Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The United Kingdom is seen as having a "natural" relationship with Israel because of the Mandate for Palestine.
[src:israel/israel-p02] By 2007, Germany had paid 25 billion euros in reparations to Israel and individual Israeli Holocaust survivors.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel is included in the European Union's European Neighbourhood Policy.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Although Turkey and Israel did not establish full diplomatic relations until 1991, Turkey has cooperated with the Jewish state since its recognition of Israel in 1949.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Turkey's ties to other Muslim-majority nations in the region have at times resulted in pressure from Arab and Muslim states to temper its relationship with Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Relations took a downturn after the 2008–09 Gaza War and Israel's raid of the Gaza flotilla.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Relations between Greece and Israel have improved since 1995 after decline of Israeli–Turkish relations.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The two countries have a defence cooperation agreement and in 2010, the Israeli Air Force hosted Greece's Hellenic Air Force in a joint exercise.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The joint Cyprus-Israel oil and gas explorations centred on the Leviathan gas field are an important factor for Greece, given its strong links with Cyprus.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Cooperation in the world's longest submarine power cable, the EuroAsia Interconnector, has strengthened Cyprus–Israel relations.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Azerbaijan is one of the few majority Muslim countries to develop strategic and economic relations with Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Kazakhstan also has an economic and strategic partnership with Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p02] India established full diplomatic ties with Israel in 1992 and has fostered a strong military, technological and cultural partnership with the country since then.
[src:israel/israel-p02] India is the largest customer of the Israeli military equipment, and Israel is the second-largest military partner of India after Russia.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Ethiopia is Israel's main ally in Africa due to common political, religious and security interests.
[src:israel/israel-p02] As of 2025, Israel is the only UN member state to recognise the Republic of Somaliland.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel has a history of providing emergency foreign aid and humanitarian response to disasters across the world.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In 1955 Israel began its foreign aid programme in Burma and then shifted to Africa.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel's humanitarian efforts officially began in 1957 with the establishment of Mashav, the Israel's Agency for International Development Cooperation.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In this early period, whilst Israel's aid represented only a small percentage of total aid to Africa, its programme was effective in creating goodwill; however, following the 1967 war relations soured.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel's foreign aid programme subsequently shifted its focus to Latin America.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Since the late 1970s Israel's foreign aid has gradually decreased, although in recent years Israel has tried to reestablish aid to Africa.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Between 1985 and 2015, Israel sent 24 delegations of their search and rescue unit the Home Front Command to 22 countries.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Currently Israeli foreign aid ranks low among OECD nations, spending less than 0.1% of its GNI on development assistance.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The country ranked 38th in the 2018 World Giving Index.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The Israel Defence Forces (IDF) is the sole military wing of the Israeli security forces and is headed by its Chief of the General Staff, the *Ramatkal*, subordinate to the Cabinet.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The IDF consists of the army, air force and navy.
[src:israel/israel-p02] It was founded during the 1948 Arab–Israeli War by consolidating paramilitary organisations, chiefly the Haganah.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The IDF also draws upon the resources of the Military Intelligence Directorate (*Aman*).
[src:israel/israel-p02] Most Israelis are conscripted at age 18.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Men serve two years and eight months, and women serve two years.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Following mandatory service, Israeli men join the reserve forces and usually do up to several weeks of reserve duty every year until their forties.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Most women are exempt from reserve duty.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Arab citizens of Israel (except the Druze) and those engaged in full-time religious studies are exempt, although the exemption of yeshiva students has been a source of contention.
[src:israel/israel-p02] An alternative for those who receive exemptions on various grounds is *Sherut Leumi*, or national service, which involves a programme of service in social welfare frameworks.
[src:israel/israel-p02] A small minority of Israeli Arabs also volunteer in the army.
[src:israel/israel-p02] As a result of its conscription programme, the IDF maintains approximately 176,500 active troops and 465,000 reservists, giving Israel one of the world's highest percentage of citizens with military training.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The military relies heavily on high-tech weapons systems designed and manufactured in Israel as well as some foreign imports.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The Arrow missile is one of the world's few operational anti-ballistic missile systems.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The Python air-to-air missile series is often considered one of the most crucial weapons in its military history.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel's Spike missile is one of the most widely exported anti-tank guided missiles in the world.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel's Iron Dome anti-missile air defence system gained worldwide acclaim after intercepting hundreds of rockets fired by Palestinian militants from the Gaza Strip.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Since the Yom Kippur War, Israel has developed a network of reconnaissance satellites.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The *Ofeq* programme has made Israel one of seven countries capable of launching such satellites.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel is widely believed to possess nuclear weapons and per a 1993 report, chemical and biological weapons of mass destruction.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel has not signed the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons and maintains a policy of deliberate ambiguity towards its nuclear capabilities.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The Israeli Navy's Dolphin submarines are believed to be armed with nuclear missiles offering second-strike capability.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Since the Gulf War in 1991, all homes in Israel are required to have a reinforced security room, Merkhav Mugan, impermeable to chemical and biological substances.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Since Israel's establishment, military expenditure constituted a significant portion of the country's gross domestic product, with peak of 30.3% of GDP in 1975.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In 2021, Israel ranked 15th in the world by total military expenditure, with $24.3 billion, and 6th by defence spending as a percentage of GDP, with 5.2%.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Since 1974, the United States has been a particularly notable contributor of military aid.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Under a memorandum of understanding signed in 2016, the U.S. is expected to provide the country with $3.8 billion per year, or around 20% of Israel's defence budget, from 2018 to 2028.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel ranked 8th globally for arms exports in 2020–2024.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The majority of Israel's arms exports are unreported for security reasons.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel is consistently rated low in the Global Peace Index, ranking 134th out of 163 nations in 2022.
[src:israel/israel-p02] At the lowest level are magistrate courts, situated in most cities across the country.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Above them are district courts, serving as both appellate courts and courts of first instance; they are situated in five of Israel's six districts.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The third and highest tier is the Supreme Court, located in Jerusalem; it serves a dual role as the highest court of appeals and the High Court of Justice.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In the latter role, the Supreme Court rules as a court of first instance, allowing both citizens and non-citizens to petition against the decisions of state authorities.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The legal system combines three legal traditions: English common law, civil law, and Jewish law.
[src:israel/israel-p02] It is based on the principle of *stare decisis* (precedent) and is an adversarial system.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Court cases are decided by professional judges.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Marriage and divorce are under the jurisdiction of the religious courts: Jewish, Muslim, Druze, and Christian.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The election of judges is carried out by a selection committee chaired by the justice minister (currently Yariv Levin).
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel's Basic Law: Human Dignity and Liberty seeks to defend human rights and liberties in Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The United Nations Human Rights Council and Israeli human rights organisation Adalah have highlighted that this law does not in fact contain a general provision for equality and non-discrimination.
[src:israel/israel-p02] As a result of "Enclave law", large portions of Israeli civil law are applied to Israeli settlements and Israeli residents in the occupied territories.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israeli law is seldom enforced in the occupied territories, with 96% of police investigations into settler violence in the West Bank from 2020 to 2025 ending without an indictment.
[src:israel/israel-p02] No one has been charged in the killings of at least 1,100 Palestinian civilians by Israeli soldiers and settlers since 2020.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel is considered the most advanced country in West Asia and the Middle East in economic and industrial development.
[src:israel/israel-p02] As of October 2023, the IMF estimated its GDP at 521.7 billion dollars and GDP per capita at 53.2 thousand (ranking 13th worldwide).
[src:israel/israel-p02] It is the third richest country in Asia by nominal per capita income and has the highest average wealth per adult in the Middle East.
[src:israel/israel-p02] *The Economist* ranked Israel as the fourth most successful economy among the developed countries for 2022.
[src:israel/israel-p02] It has the most billionaires in the Middle East and the 18th most in the world.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In recent years, Israel had one of the highest growth rates in the developed world.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The country is ranked 35th on the World Bank's *Ease of Doing Business* index.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Economic data covers the economic territory of Israel, including the Golan Heights, East Jerusalem and Israeli settlements in the West Bank.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Despite limited natural resources, intensive development of the agricultural and industrial sectors over the past decades has made Israel largely self-sufficient in food production, apart from grains and beef.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Imports, totalling $96.5 billion in 2020, include raw materials, military equipment, investment goods, rough diamonds, fuels, grain, and consumer goods.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Leading exports include machinery, equipment, software, cut diamonds, agricultural products, chemicals, textiles, and apparel; in 2020, exports reached $114 billion.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The Bank of Israel holds $201 billion of foreign-exchange reserves, the 17th highest in the world.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Since the 1970s, Israel has received military aid from the United States, as well as loan guarantees, which account for roughly half of Israel's external debt.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel has one of the lowest external debts in the developed world, and is a lender in terms of net external debt (assets vs. liabilities abroad), which in 2015 stood at a surplus of $69 billion.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel has the second-largest number of startup companies after the United States and the third-largest number of NASDAQ-listed companies.
[src:israel/israel-p02] It is the world leader for number of start-ups per capita and has been dubbed the "Start-Up Nation".
[src:israel/israel-p02] Intel and Microsoft built their first overseas research and development facilities in Israel, and other high-tech multinational corporations have opened research and development centres in the country.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The days which are allocated to working times are Sunday through Thursday (for a five-day workweek), or Friday (for a six-day workweek).
[src:israel/israel-p02] In observance of Shabbat, in places where Friday is a work day and the majority of population is Jewish, Friday is a "short day".
[src:israel/israel-p02] Several proposals have been raised to adjust the work week with the majority of the world.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel's development of cutting-edge technologies in software, communications and the life sciences have evoked comparisons with Silicon Valley.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel is first in the world in expenditure on research and development as a percentage of GDP.
[src:israel/israel-p02] It is ranked 14th in the Global Innovation Index in 2025, and 5th in the 2019 Bloomberg Innovation Index.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israeli universities are ranked among the top 50 world universities in computer science (Technion and Tel Aviv University), mathematics (Hebrew University of Jerusalem) and chemistry (Weizmann Institute of Science).
[src:israel/israel-p02] In 2012, Israel was ranked ninth in the world by the Futron's Space Competitiveness Index.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The Israel Space Agency coordinates all space research programmes with scientific and commercial goals, and have designed and built at least 13 commercial, research and spy satellites.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Some satellites are ranked among the world's most advanced space systems.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Shavit is a space launch vehicle produced by Israel to launch small satellites into low Earth orbit.
[src:israel/israel-p02] It was first launched in 1988, making Israel the eighth nation to have a space launch capability.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In 2003, Ilan Ramon became Israel's first astronaut, serving on the fatal mission of Space Shuttle *Columbia*.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The ongoing water shortage has spurred innovation in water conservation techniques, and a substantial agricultural modernisation, drip irrigation, was invented in Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel is also at the technological forefront of desalination and water recycling.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The Sorek desalination plant is the largest seawater reverse osmosis desalination facility in the world.
[src:israel/israel-p02] By 2014, desalination programmes provided roughly 35% of the drinking water, and it is expected to supply 70% by 2050.
[src:israel/israel-p02] As of 2015, over 50 per cent of the water for households, agriculture and industry is artificially produced.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In 2011, Israel's water technology industry was worth around $2 billion per year with annual exports of products and services in the tens of millions of dollars.
[src:israel/israel-p02] As a result of innovations in reverse osmosis technology, Israel is set to become a net exporter of water.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel has embraced solar energy; its engineers are on the cutting edge of solar energy technology, and its solar companies work on projects around the world.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Over 90% of homes use solar energy for hot water, the highest per capita.
[src:israel/israel-p02] According to government figures, the country saves 8% of its electricity consumption per year because of its solar energy use in heating.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The high annual incident solar irradiance at its geographic latitude creates ideal conditions for what is an internationally renowned solar research and development industry in the Negev.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel had a modern electric car infrastructure involving a countrywide network of charging stations; however, its electric car company Better Place shut down in 2013.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel began producing natural gas from its own offshore gas fields in 2004.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In 2009 Tamar gas field was discovered near the coast, and Leviathan gas field was discovered in 2010.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The natural gas reserves in these two fields could make Israel energy-secure for more than 50 years.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Commercial production of natural gas from the Tamar field began in 2013, with over 7.5 billion cubic metres (bcm) produced annually.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel had 199 billion bcm of proven reserves of natural gas as of 2016.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The Leviathan gas field started production in 2019.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Ketura Sun is Israel's first commercial solar field.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Built in 2011 by the Arava Power Company, the field will produce about 9 gigawatt-hours (32 TJ) of electricity per year, sparing the production of some 125,000 tonnes (123,000 long tons; 138,000 short tons) of carbon dioxide over 20 years.
[src:israel/israel-p02] As of 2016, Israel has 19,224 kilometres (11,945 mi) of paved roads and 3 million motor vehicles.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The number of motor vehicles per 1,000 persons is 365, relatively low among developed countries.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The country aims to have 30% of vehicles on its roads powered by electricity by 2030.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel has 5,715 buses on scheduled routes, operated by several carriers, the largest and oldest of which is Egged, serving most of the country.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Railways stretch across 1,277 kilometres (793 mi) and are operated by government-owned Israel Railways.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Following major investments beginning in the early to mid-1990s, the number of train passengers per year has grown from 2.5 million in 1990, to 53 million in 2015; railways transport 7.5 million tonnes (8.3 million short tons; 7.4 million long tons) of cargo per year.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel is served by three international airports: Ben Gurion Airport, the country's main hub for international air travel; Ramon Airport; and Haifa Airport.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Ben Gurion handled over 21.1 million passengers in 2023.
[src:israel/israel-p02] There are three main ports: the Port of Haifa, the oldest and largest; Ashdod Port; and the Port of Eilat on the Red Sea.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Tourism, especially religious tourism, is an important industry, with beaches, archaeological, other historical and biblical sites, and unique geography also drawing tourists.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In 2017, a record 3.6 million tourists visited Israel, yielding a 25 per cent growth since 2016 and contributed NIS 20 billion to the economy.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Housing prices are listed in the top third of all countries, with an average of 150 salaries required to buy an apartment.
[src:israel/israel-p02] As of 2022, there are about 2.7 million properties in Israel, with an annual increase of over 50,000.
[src:israel/israel-p02] However, demand for housing exceeds supply, with a shortage of about 200,000 apartments as of 2021.
[src:israel/israel-p02] As a result, by 2021 housing prices rose by 5.6%.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In 2021, Israelis took a record of NIS 116.1 billion in mortgages, an increase of 50% from 2020.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel has the largest Jewish population in the world and is the only country where Jews are the majority.
[src:israel/israel-p02] As of April 2025, the population was an estimated 10,094,000.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In 2025, the government recorded 72% of the population as Jews, 21% as Arabs, and 7% as "Others" (non-Arab Christians and people who have no religion listed).
[src:israel/israel-p02] Over the last decade, large numbers of migrant workers from Romania, Thailand, China, Africa, and South America have settled in Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Exact figures are unknown, as many of them are living in the country illegally, but estimates run from 166,000 to 203,000.
[src:israel/israel-p02] By June 2012, approximately 60,000 African migrants had entered Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p02] About 93% of Israelis live in urban areas.
[src:israel/israel-p02] 90% of Palestinian Israelis reside in 139 densely populated towns and villages concentrated in the Galilee, Triangle and Negev regions, with the remaining 10% in mixed cities and neighbourhoods.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The OECD in 2016 estimated the average life expectancy at 82.5 years, the 6th-highest in the world.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israeli Arab life expectancy lags by 3 to 4 years and is higher than in most Arab and Muslim countries.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The country has the highest fertility rate in the OECD and the only one which is above the replacement figure of 2.1.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Retention of Israel's population since 1948 is about even or greater, when compared to other countries with mass immigration.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Jewish emigration from Israel (called *yerida*), primarily to the United States and Canada, is described by demographers as modest, but is often cited by Israeli government ministries as a major threat to Israel's future.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Approximately 80% of Israeli Jews are born in Israel, 14% are immigrants from Europe and the Americas, and 6% are immigrants from Asia and Africa.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Jews from Europe and the former Soviet Union and their descendants born in Israel, including Ashkenazi Jews, constitute approximately 44% of Jewish Israelis.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Jews from Arab and Muslim countries and their descendants, including both Mizrahi and Sephardi Jews, form most of the rest of the Jewish population.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Jewish intermarriage rates run at over 35% and recent studies suggest that the percentage of Israelis descended from both Sephardi and Ashkenazi Jews increases by 0.5 per cent yearly, with over 25% of schoolchildren now originating from both.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Around 4% of Israelis (300,000), ethnically defined as "others", are Russian descendants of Jewish origin or family who are not Jewish according to rabbinical law, but were eligible for citizenship under the Law of Return.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israeli settlers beyond the Green Line number over 600,000 (≈10% of the Jewish Israeli population).
[src:israel/israel-p02] In 2016, 399,300 Israelis lived in West Bank settlements, including those that predated the establishment of the State of Israel and which were re-established after the Six-Day War.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Additionally there were more than 200,000 Jews living in East Jerusalem and 22,000 in the Golan Heights.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Approximately 7,800 Israelis lived in settlements in the Gaza Strip, known as Gush Katif, until they were evacuated by the government as part of its 2005 disengagement plan.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israeli Arabs (including the Arab population of East Jerusalem and the Golan Heights) comprise 21.1% of the population or 1,995,000 people.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel has four major metropolitan areas: Gush Dan (Tel Aviv metropolitan area; population 3,854,000), Jerusalem (population 1,253,900), Haifa (924,400), and Beersheba (377,100).
[src:israel/israel-p02] The largest municipality, in population and area, is Jerusalem with 1,050,153 residents in an area of 125 square kilometres (48 sq mi).
[src:israel/israel-p02] Statistics on Jerusalem include the population and area of East Jerusalem, the status of which is in international dispute.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Tel Aviv and Haifa rank as Israel's next most populous cities, with populations of 494,900 and 297,082, respectively.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The (mainly Haredi) city of Bnei Brak is the most densely populated city in Israel and one of the 10 most densely populated cities in the world.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel has 16 cities with populations over 100,000.
[src:israel/israel-p02] As of 2018 there are 77 localities granted "municipalities" (or "city") status by the Ministry of the Interior, four of which are in the West Bank.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Hebrew is the primary language of the state and is spoken daily by the majority of the population.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Prior to 1948, opposition to Yiddish, the historical language of the Ashkenazi Jews, was common among supporters of the Zionist movement, including the Yishuv, who sought to promote Hebrew's revival as a unifying national language.
[src:israel/israel-p02] These sentiments were reflected in the early policies of the Israeli government, which largely banned Yiddish theatre and publications.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Until 2018, Arabic was also an official language; in 2018 it was downgraded to having a "special status in the state".
[src:israel/israel-p02] Arabic is spoken by the Arab minority and is the main medium of teaching in Arab schools where Hebrew is studied as a subject.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Arabic is studied in most Jewish schools and is often used on signage and in transport announcements.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Due to mass immigration from the former Soviet Union and Ethiopia (some 130,000 Ethiopian Jews live in Israel), Russian and Amharic are widely spoken.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Over one million Russian-speaking immigrants arrived in Israel between 1990 and 2004.
[src:israel/israel-p02] French is spoken by around 700,000 Israelis, mostly originating from France and North Africa (see Maghrebi Jews).
[src:israel/israel-p02] English was an official language during the Mandate period; it lost this status after the establishment of Israel, but retains a role comparable to that of an official language.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Many Israelis communicate reasonably well in English, as many television programmes are broadcast in English with subtitles and the language is taught in elementary school.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The primary medium of teaching in Israeli universities is Hebrew, but some courses are offered in English.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The main language of the Circassians in Israel is Adyghe, and most of them also know Hebrew and Arabic.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The deaf community in Israel primarily uses the Israeli Sign Language.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Several village sign languages are used in Israel, most notably the Al-Sayyid Bedouin Sign Language and the Kafr Qasem Sign Language.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The estimated religious affiliation as of 2022 was 73.5% Jewish, 18.1% Muslim, 1.9% Christian, 1.6% Druze, and 4.9% other.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The religious affiliation of Israeli Jews varies widely: a 2016 survey by Pew Research indicates that 49% self-identify as Hiloni (secular), 29% as Masorti (traditional), 13% as Dati (religious) and 9% as Haredi (ultra-Orthodox).
[src:israel/israel-p02] Haredi Jews are expected to represent over 20% of the Jewish population by 2028.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Muslims constitute the largest religious minority, making up about 18.1% of the population.
[src:israel/israel-p02] About 1.9% of the population is Christian, and 1.6% is Druze.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The Christian population comprises primarily Arab Christians and Aramean Christians but also includes post-Soviet immigrants, foreign labourers, Armenian Christians, and followers of Messianic Judaism, considered by most Christians and Jews to be a form of Christianity.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Members of many other religious groups, including Buddhists and Hindus, maintain a presence in Israel, albeit in small numbers.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Out of over one million immigrants from the former Soviet Union, about 300,000 are considered not Jewish by the Chief Rabbinate of Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel comprises a major part of the Holy Land, a region of significant importance to all Abrahamic religions.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Jerusalem is of special importance to Jews, Muslims, and Christians, as it is the home of sites that are pivotal to their religious beliefs, such as the Old City that incorporates the Western Wall and the Temple Mount (Al-Aqsa Mosque compound) and the Church of the Holy Sepulchre.
[src:israel/israel-p02] A number of other religious landmarks are located in the West Bank, including Joseph's Tomb, the birthplace of Jesus, Rachel's Tomb, and the Cave of the Patriarchs.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The administrative center of the Baháʼí Faith and the Shrine of the Báb are located at the Baháʼí World Centre in Haifa; the leader of the faith is buried in Acre.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The Mahmood Mosque is affiliated with the reformist Ahmadiyya movement.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Kababir, Haifa's mixed neighbourhood of Jews and Ahmadi Arabs, is one of a few of its kind in the country.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In 2015, Israel ranked third among OECD members for the percentage of 25–64-year-olds that have attained tertiary education with 49% compared with the OECD average of 35%.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In 2012, the country ranked third in the number of academic degrees per capita (20 per cent of the population).
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel has a school life expectancy of 16 years and a literacy rate of 97.8%.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The State Education Law (1953) established five types of schools: state secular, state religious, ultra orthodox, communal settlement schools, and Arab schools.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The public secular is the largest school group and is attended by the majority of Jewish and non-Arab pupils.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Most Arabs send their children to Arabic-language schools.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Education is compulsory between the ages of three and eighteen.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Schooling is divided into three tiers—primary school (grades 1–6), middle school (grades 7–9), and high school (grades 10–12)—culminating with *Bagrut* matriculation exams.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Proficiency in core subjects such as mathematics, the Hebrew language, Hebrew and general literature, the English language, history, Biblical scripture and civics is necessary to receive a Bagrut certificate.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The Jewish population maintains a relatively high level of educational attainment where just under half of all Israeli Jews (46%) hold post-secondary degrees.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israeli Jews 25 and older have an average 11.6 years of schooling, making them one of the most highly educated of all major religious groups in the world.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In Arab, Christian and Druze schools, the exam on Biblical studies is replaced by an exam on Muslim, Christian or Druze heritage, respectively.
[src:israel/israel-p02] In 2020, 68.7% of 12th graders earned a matriculation certificate.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel has a tradition of higher education where its university education has been largely responsible in spurring modern economic development.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Israel has nine public universities subsidised by the state and 49 private colleges.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The Hebrew University of Jerusalem houses the National Library of Israel, the world's largest repository of Judaica and Hebraica.
[src:israel/israel-p02] The Technion and the Hebrew University consistently ranked among world's 100 top universities by ARWU ranking.
[src:israel/israel-p02] Other major universities include the Weizmann Institute of Science, Tel Aviv University, Ben-Gurion University of the Negev, Bar-Ilan University, the University of Haifa, and the Open University of Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Cultural diversity stems from its diverse population: Jews from various diaspora communities brought their cultural and religious traditions with them.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Arab influences are found in architecture, music, and cuisine, among others.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Israel is the only country where life revolves around the Hebrew calendar, which is aligned to the seasons in the Levant.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Public holidays are determined by the Jewish holidays, and except for Yom HaAtzma'ut (Independence Day) there are no annual civil holidays.
[src:israel/israel-p03] The official day of rest is Saturday, the Jewish Sabbath.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Israeli literature is primarily poetry and prose written in Hebrew, as part of the renaissance of Hebrew as a spoken language since the mid-19th century, although a small body of literature is published in other languages.
[src:israel/israel-p03] By law, two copies of all works published in Israel must be deposited in the National Library.
[src:israel/israel-p03] In 2016, 89 per cent of the 7,300 books transferred to the library were in Hebrew.
[src:israel/israel-p03] In 1966, Shmuel Yosef Agnon shared the Nobel Prize in Literature with German Jewish author Nelly Sachs.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Leading poets include Yehuda Amichai, Nathan Alterman, Leah Goldberg, and Rachel Bluwstein.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Internationally famous contemporary novelists include Amos Oz, Etgar Keret and David Grossman.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Israeli music includes Mizrahi and Sephardic music, Hasidic melodies, Greek music, jazz, and pop rock.
[src:israel/israel-p03] The Israel Philharmonic Orchestra has been in operation for over seventy years and performs more than two hundred concerts each year.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Itzhak Perlman, Pinchas Zukerman and Ofra Haza are among the internationally acclaimed musicians born in Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p03] The country has participated in the Eurovision Song Contest nearly every year since 1973, winning it four times and hosting three times.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Eilat has hosted its own international music festival, the Red Sea Jazz Festival, every summer since 1987.
[src:israel/israel-p03] The nation's canonical folk songs are known as "Songs of the Land of Israel".
[src:israel/israel-p03] Ten Israeli films have been final nominees for Best Foreign Language Film at the Academy Awards.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Palestinian Israeli filmmakers have made films dealing with the Arab-Israeli conflict and status of Palestinians within Israel, such as Mohammad Bakri's 2002 film *Jenin, Jenin* and *The Syrian Bride*.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Continuing the strong theatrical traditions of the Yiddish theatre in Eastern Europe, Israel maintains a vibrant theatre scene.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Founded in 1918, Habima Theatre in Tel Aviv is Israel's oldest repertory theatre company and national theatre.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Other theatres include Ohel, the Cameri and Gesher.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Israeli Jewish art has been particularly influenced by the Kabbalah, the Talmud and the Zohar.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Another art movement that held a prominent role in the 20th century was the School of Paris.
[src:israel/israel-p03] In the late 19th and early 20th century, the Yishuv's art was dominated by art trends emanating Bezalel.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Beginning in the 1920s, the local art scene was heavily influenced by modern French art, first introduced by Isaac Frenkel Frenel.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Jewish masters of the school of Paris, such as Soutine, Kikoine, Frenkel, Chagall heavily influenced the development of Israeli art.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Israeli sculpture took inspiration from modern European sculpture as well Mesopotamian, Assyrian and local art.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Avraham Melnikov's The Roaring Lion, David Polus' Alexander Zaid and Ze'ev Ben Zvi's cubist sculpture exemplify some of the different streams in sculpture.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Common themes in art are the mystical cities of Safed and Jerusalem, the bohemian café culture of Tel Aviv, agricultural landscapes, biblical stories and war.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Today Israeli art has delved into optical art, AI art, digital art and the use of salt in sculpture.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Due to the immigration of Jewish architects, architecture has come to reflect different styles.
[src:israel/israel-p03] In the early 20th century Jewish architects sought to combine Occidental and Oriental architecture producing buildings that showcase a myriad of infused styles.
[src:israel/israel-p03] The eclectic style gave way to the modernist Bauhaus style with the influx of German Jewish architects (among them Erich Mendelsohn) fleeing Nazi persecution.
[src:israel/israel-p03] The White City of Tel Aviv is a UNESCO heritage site.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Following independence, multiple government projects were commissioned, a grand part built in a brutalist style with heavy emphasis on the use of concrete and acclimatisation to the desert climate.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Several novel ideas such as the Garden City were implemented in Israeli cities; the Geddes plan of Tel Aviv became renowned internationally for its revolutionary design and adaptation to the local climate.
[src:israel/israel-p03] The Israel Museum in Jerusalem is one of Israel's most important cultural institutions, and houses the Dead Sea Scrolls, along with an extensive collection of Judaica and European art.
[src:israel/israel-p03] 'a memorial and a name') is the world's central Holocaust memorial institution and archive of Holocaust-related information.
[src:israel/israel-p03] ANU - Museum of the Jewish People is an interactive museum devoted to the history of Jewish communities around the world.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Israel has the highest number of museums per capita.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Several museums are devoted to Islamic culture, including the Rockefeller Archaeological Museum and the L.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Mayer Institute for Islamic Art, both in Jerusalem.
[src:israel/israel-p03] The Rockefeller specialises in archaeological remains from Middle East history.
[src:israel/israel-p03] It is also the home of the first hominid fossil skull found in West Asia, called Galilee Man.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Notable newspapers include the left-wing *Haaretz*, centrist *Yedioth Ahronoth*, and center-right *Israel Hayom*.
[src:israel/israel-p03] There are several major television channels which cater to different audiences, from Russian-language Channel 9 to Arabic-language Kan 33.
[src:israel/israel-p03] The 2024 Freedom House report found Israeli media is "vibrant and free to criticise government policy".
[src:israel/israel-p03] In the 2024 Press Freedom Index by Reporters Without Borders, Israel was placed 112th of 180 countries, second in the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Reporters Without Borders reported that the Israel Defence Forces had killed more than 100 Palestinian journalists in Gaza.
[src:israel/israel-p03] During the 2023 Gaza war, Israel has been alleged to be "trying to suppress the reporting coming out of the besieged enclave while disinformation infiltrates its own media ecosystem".
[src:israel/israel-p03] In May 2024, Israel shut down the local offices of Al Jazeera.
[src:israel/israel-p03] In 2024, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, Israel was the second leading country in jailing journalists, and responsible for the majority of journalists killed in the world.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Israeli cuisine includes local dishes as well as Jewish cuisine brought to the country by immigrants.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Particularly since the late 1970s, a fusion cuisine has developed.
[src:israel/israel-p03] The cuisine has adapted elements of the Mizrahi, Sephardi, and Ashkenazi styles of cooking.
[src:israel/israel-p03] It incorporates many foods traditionally eaten in the Levantine, Arab, Middle Eastern and Mediterranean cuisines, such as falafel, hummus, shakshouka, couscous, and za'atar.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Schnitzel, pizza, hamburgers, French fries, rice and salad are common.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Ptitim (Israeli couscous) is a notable Israeli food invented in the 1950s due to rice shortages during the austerity period.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Roughly half of the Jewish population attests to keeping kosher at home.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Kosher restaurants make up around a quarter of the total as of 2015.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Pork—often called "white meat" in Israel—is produced and consumed despite attempts to ban it; it is forbidden by both Judaism and Islam but is permitted by Christianity and mostly produced in traditionally Christian areas of northern Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Other non-kosher foods produced and eaten in Israel include rabbits, ostriches, and non-kosher fish.
[src:israel/israel-p03] The most popular spectator sports in Israel are association football and basketball.
[src:israel/israel-p03] The Israeli Premier League is the country's premier football league, and the Israeli Basketball Premier League is the premier basketball league.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Maccabi Haifa, Maccabi Tel Aviv, Hapoel Tel Aviv and Beitar Jerusalem are the largest football clubs.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Maccabi Tel Aviv, Maccabi Haifa and Hapoel Tel Aviv have competed in the UEFA Champions League and Hapoel Tel Aviv reached the UEFA Cup quarter-finals.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Israel hosted and won the 1964 AFC Asian Cup; in 1970 the Israel national football team qualified for the FIFA World Cup, the only time it participated.
[src:israel/israel-p03] The 1974 Asian Games, held in Tehran, were the last Asian Games in which Israel participated, plagued by Arab countries that refused to compete with Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Israel was excluded from the 1978 Asian Games and since then has not competed in Asian sport events.
[src:israel/israel-p03] In 1994, UEFA agreed to admit Israel, and its football teams now compete in Europe.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Maccabi Tel Aviv B.C. has won the European championship in basketball six times.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Israel has won 20 Olympic medals since its first win in 1992, including a gold medal in windsurfing at the 2004 Summer Olympics, and seven medals at the 2024 Paris Olympics.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Israel has won over 100 gold medals in the Paralympic Games and is ranked 20th in the all-time medal count.
[src:israel/israel-p03] The 1968 Summer Paralympics were hosted by Israel.
[src:israel/israel-p03] The Maccabiah Games, an Olympic-style event for Jewish and Israeli athletes, has been held every four years since the 1930s.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Krav Maga, a martial art developed by Jewish ghetto defenders, is used by the Israeli security forces and police.
[src:israel/israel-p03] There are many Israeli grandmasters and Israeli chess players have won a number of youth world championships.
[src:israel/israel-p03] Israel stages an annual international championship and hosted the World Team Chess Championship in 2005.
